194
00:10:46,840 --> 00:10:49,560
And I guess we will start at
a very high level, because I

195
00:10:49,560 --> 00:10:56,080
will just assume that I guess
we're starting from scratch.

196
00:10:56,080 --> 00:11:00,480
And we're going to talk
about NLP in general.

197
00:11:00,480 --> 00:11:03,500
So NLP is going to be
our first abbreviation.

198
00:11:03,500 --> 00:11:07,600
So NLP stands for Natural
Language Processing.

199
00:11:07,600 --> 00:11:12,420
And it is a field that is
around manipulating text,

200
00:11:12,420 --> 00:11:15,600
just computing things with text.

201
00:11:15,600 --> 00:11:20,440
And at a very high level, can
basically classify NLP tasks

202
00:11:20,440 --> 00:11:22,600
into three buckets.

203
00:11:22,600 --> 00:11:26,520
So the first bucket is what
we call classification.

204
00:11:26,520 --> 00:11:30,240
So we have an input
text as an input.

205
00:11:30,240 --> 00:11:34,520
And then what we want
is to predict something.

206
00:11:34,520 --> 00:11:38,000
So one example is you
have a movie review

207
00:11:38,000 --> 00:11:42,190
and you want to predict whether
the sentiment is positive,

208
00:11:42,190 --> 00:11:44,250
negative, or neutral.

209
00:11:44,250 --> 00:11:46,090
So that's one example.

210
00:11:46,090 --> 00:11:50,198
You can also have intent
detection, just knowing

211
00:11:50,198 --> 00:11:51,990
what, for instance,
the person wants to do.

212
00:11:51,990 --> 00:11:55,930
So let's suppose you say, I want
to create an alarm for tomorrow.

213
00:11:55,930 --> 00:11:59,650
So the intent here
is create an alarm.

214
00:11:59,650 --> 00:12:01,830
So also to detect a
language-- so for instance,

215
00:12:01,830 --> 00:12:03,770
if you write among
French, you want

216
00:12:03,770 --> 00:12:09,930
to detect that text is in
French, topic modeling.

217
00:12:09,930 --> 00:12:14,210
The second category is what
we call multi-classification.

218
00:12:14,210 --> 00:12:17,370
So we still have
a text as input,

219
00:12:17,370 --> 00:12:21,570
but this time we predict
more than one thing.

220
00:12:21,570 --> 00:12:25,330
So you have a number of
tasks in that bucket as well.

221
00:12:25,330 --> 00:12:30,130
So one that is very popular is
called Named Entity Recognition,

222
00:12:30,130 --> 00:12:31,116
a.k.a.

223
00:12:31,116 --> 00:12:33,210
NER.

224
00:12:33,210 --> 00:12:37,290
So what that task does
is, given an input text,

225
00:12:37,290 --> 00:12:41,070
we want to basically label
some specific words, like,

226
00:12:41,070 --> 00:12:43,270
for instance, identifying
whether something

227
00:12:43,270 --> 00:12:49,070
is a location, or
a time, and so on.

228
00:12:49,070 --> 00:12:50,950
And then you have some
other tasks as well

229
00:12:50,950 --> 00:12:53,790
that are a little bit more
on the linguistic side.

230
00:12:53,790 --> 00:12:55,710
I think they're less
trendy now, but I

231
00:12:55,710 --> 00:12:57,630
guess 10 years ago
it was something

232
00:12:57,630 --> 00:13:00,030
that people would study a lot.

233
00:13:00,030 --> 00:13:04,070
So part of speech tagging, which
is about just figuring out which

234
00:13:04,070 --> 00:13:07,030
word is a noun, a
verb, et cetera,

235
00:13:07,030 --> 00:13:10,910
or some parsing-related tasks,
so dependency or constituency

236
00:13:10,910 --> 00:13:13,510
parsing.

237
00:13:13,510 --> 00:13:19,110
And then the last bucket, which
is very popular these days is

238
00:13:19,110 --> 00:13:21,710
the generation bucket.

239
00:13:21,710 --> 00:13:25,350
So you have the text
as input, and you also

240
00:13:25,350 --> 00:13:28,110
have text as output.

241
00:13:28,110 --> 00:13:30,130
And here the length
can be variable,

242
00:13:30,130 --> 00:13:33,150
meaning you don't know what
the length of your output text

243
00:13:33,150 --> 00:13:35,430
will be beforehand.

244
00:13:35,430 --> 00:13:37,500
So here you have several tasks.

245
00:13:37,500 --> 00:13:39,968
So for instance, you
have machine translation.

246
00:13:39,968 --> 00:13:41,760
So for instance,
something in English and I

247
00:13:41,760 --> 00:13:44,960
wanted to let's say German.

248
00:13:44,960 --> 00:13:46,880
Question answering--
so typically

249
00:13:46,880 --> 00:13:50,300
the ChatGPT, Gemini that
you're using, the assistant.

250
00:13:50,300 --> 00:13:54,120
So you ask a question
and you have a response.

251
00:13:54,120 --> 00:13:58,500
And then you have other tasks
as well, like summarization,

252
00:13:58,500 --> 00:14:00,800
you want to summarize
an article, let's say,

253
00:14:00,800 --> 00:14:02,840
or just generate something.

254
00:14:02,840 --> 00:14:07,040
So something can be generate
codes, generate a poem,

255
00:14:07,040 --> 00:14:08,420
can also be a lot of things.

256
00:14:11,000 --> 00:14:11,740
Cool.

257
00:14:11,740 --> 00:14:16,920
So now what we will do is go
through these tasks one by one

258
00:14:16,920 --> 00:14:21,840
to just illustrate what
people typically handle with.

259
00:14:21,840 --> 00:14:25,000
So we're going to start
with the first bucket, which

260
00:14:25,000 --> 00:14:27,800
is the classification bucket.

261
00:14:27,800 --> 00:14:29,640
And here we're
going to illustrate

262
00:14:29,640 --> 00:14:32,600
this with the sentiment
extraction task.

263
00:14:32,600 --> 00:14:35,800
So let's suppose
we have a sentence,

264
00:14:35,800 --> 00:14:37,700
"this teddy bear is so cute."

265
00:14:37,700 --> 00:14:43,380
We want our model to predict
this to be a positive sentiment.

266
00:14:43,380 --> 00:14:47,540
So typically what you
would use is sentiment

267
00:14:47,540 --> 00:14:48,520
extraction data sets.

268
00:14:48,520 --> 00:14:52,620
So I mentioned movie reviews,
so this is IMDb critiques.

269
00:14:52,620 --> 00:14:54,760
But you also have
reviews about products,

270
00:14:54,760 --> 00:14:58,620
so Amazon reviews or tweets.

271
00:14:58,620 --> 00:15:03,260
Now I guess it's
called X, so X posts.

272
00:15:03,260 --> 00:15:07,300
And the way you would
evaluate such outputs

273
00:15:07,300 --> 00:15:11,660
would be by typically using
traditional classification

274
00:15:11,660 --> 00:15:13,540
metrics.

275
00:15:13,540 --> 00:15:16,380
So you have accuracy,
which is what

276
00:15:16,380 --> 00:15:17,980
is the percentage
of the observations

277
00:15:17,980 --> 00:15:21,220
that you correctly predicted.

278
00:15:21,220 --> 00:15:23,860
But you also have
two key metrics,

279
00:15:23,860 --> 00:15:26,050
which I'm just going to remind.

280
00:15:26,050 --> 00:15:27,800
I'm not sure if everyone
knows about them.

281
00:15:27,800 --> 00:15:31,700
So one is precision,
which is, out of all

282
00:15:31,700 --> 00:15:34,470
the positive predictions
that you made,

283
00:15:34,470 --> 00:15:37,470
which ones were correct?

284
00:15:37,470 --> 00:15:39,990
And then the second
one is recall.

285
00:15:39,990 --> 00:15:44,390
Out of all the true
labels, how many of them

286
00:15:44,390 --> 00:15:47,390
did you correctly predict
as being positive?

287
00:15:47,390 --> 00:15:51,430
And you have this metric
called the F1 score, which

288
00:15:51,430 --> 00:15:54,030
basically takes the
harmonic mean of precision

289
00:15:54,030 --> 00:15:57,910
and recall to just
give you one number.

290
00:15:57,910 --> 00:16:01,350
So now you may wonder, why do
you need all these metrics?

291
00:16:01,350 --> 00:16:06,030
So the short answer is that
sometimes you have tasks

292
00:16:06,030 --> 00:16:10,910
and data sets where your
classes are very imbalanced.

293
00:16:10,910 --> 00:16:14,750
So for instance, you can
have 99% of your data set

294
00:16:14,750 --> 00:16:17,950
that is a positive label,
and then only 1% of the data

295
00:16:17,950 --> 00:16:20,190
set which is negative.

296
00:16:20,190 --> 00:16:23,670
And so here if you take
a metric like accuracy,

297
00:16:23,670 --> 00:16:26,390
can be very misleading.

298
00:16:26,390 --> 00:16:30,430
Because if you have a model
that would predict everything

299
00:16:30,430 --> 00:16:34,970
as the majority class, then you
will have a great classifier,

300
00:16:34,970 --> 00:16:36,070
but that's not the case.

301
00:16:36,070 --> 00:16:41,170
So that's why precision and
recall really play a role.

302
00:16:41,170 --> 00:16:44,030
So that's for the first one.

303
00:16:44,030 --> 00:16:47,690
So now let's move to the
second category of NLP tasks.

304
00:16:47,690 --> 00:16:51,410
So this one is the
multi-classification category.

305
00:16:51,410 --> 00:16:55,930
So you have an input text and
you predict multiple things.

306
00:16:55,930 --> 00:17:01,050
And we're illustrating this
with the NER task, which

307
00:17:01,050 --> 00:17:03,890
as I mentioned is
about identifying

308
00:17:03,890 --> 00:17:07,210
the category of given words.

309
00:17:07,210 --> 00:17:10,650
And so here, for instance, we
want to identify a teddy bear

310
00:17:10,650 --> 00:17:13,089
as being an entity.

311
00:17:13,089 --> 00:17:18,609
I guess for that, you would use
classification metrics, but not

312
00:17:18,609 --> 00:17:22,930
at the sentence level, but
more either at the token level

313
00:17:22,930 --> 00:17:26,530
or at the entity-type level.

314
00:17:26,530 --> 00:17:31,140
And by that I mean, let's
suppose you have a category,

315
00:17:31,140 --> 00:17:32,280
let's say location.

316
00:17:32,280 --> 00:17:36,060
And you want to know how
well you're predicting

317
00:17:36,060 --> 00:17:37,440
words in that category.

318
00:17:37,440 --> 00:17:40,980
So you would typically
aggregate these metrics

319
00:17:40,980 --> 00:17:44,440
as a function of that.

320
00:17:44,440 --> 00:17:44,940
Cool.

321
00:17:47,580 --> 00:17:49,540
OK, let's go to the
last category, which

322
00:17:49,540 --> 00:17:51,800
is, as I mentioned,
the most popular one.

323
00:17:51,800 --> 00:17:56,660
So this one is
text in, text out.

324
00:17:56,660 --> 00:17:59,540
So I'm illustrating this
with the machine translation

325
00:17:59,540 --> 00:18:04,380
task, which is around
translating a text from a source

326
00:18:04,380 --> 00:18:07,060
language to a target language.

327
00:18:07,060 --> 00:18:09,920
So here you have the example
with English to French.

328
00:18:09,920 --> 00:18:15,180
So cute teddy bear is reading,
un ours en peluche mignon lit.

329
00:18:15,180 --> 00:18:18,580
So for that, I guess it's
harder to get data sets,

330
00:18:18,580 --> 00:18:23,700
because here you need
to have pairs of texts.

331
00:18:23,700 --> 00:18:25,580
So you have a very
popular data set

332
00:18:25,580 --> 00:18:30,280
that's called WMT, which
stands for Workshop on Machine

333
00:18:30,280 --> 00:18:32,160
Translation.

334
00:18:32,160 --> 00:18:36,360
And that one contains a
bunch of paired sequences

335
00:18:36,360 --> 00:18:38,218
in different languages.

336
00:18:38,218 --> 00:18:40,760
So for instance, you have the
English-French, English-German,

337
00:18:40,760 --> 00:18:43,800
coming from the European
Parliament data set,

338
00:18:43,800 --> 00:18:46,240
for instance.

339
00:18:46,240 --> 00:18:49,760
So to evaluate
those, to evaluate

340
00:18:49,760 --> 00:18:55,520
the performance of your model,
it's actually a lot more tricky.

341
00:18:55,520 --> 00:18:59,280
Because, as you can imagine,
you can have many different ways

342
00:18:59,280 --> 00:19:01,560
to translate something.

343
00:19:01,560 --> 00:19:07,080
I'm sure many of us in the
room are bilingual, trilingual.

344
00:19:07,080 --> 00:19:12,120
So that's what is
making it this hard.

345
00:19:12,120 --> 00:19:17,160
So in the past, people have
used several rule-based metrics

346
00:19:17,160 --> 00:19:18,720
to do that.

347
00:19:18,720 --> 00:19:22,560
So one that you may
have heard is BLEU.

348
00:19:22,560 --> 00:19:27,850
BLEU stands for Bilingual
Evaluation Under Study.

349
00:19:27,850 --> 00:19:32,970
And it is a measure of how
well your translation stands

350
00:19:32,970 --> 00:19:36,730
with respect to
a reference text.

351
00:19:36,730 --> 00:19:42,530
Same story for ROUGE, which is
actually a suite of metrics,

352
00:19:42,530 --> 00:19:45,290
but captures that
in a different way.

353
00:19:45,290 --> 00:19:48,250
And you will see that the
machine learning community

354
00:19:48,250 --> 00:19:50,110
is funny, because BLEU--

355
00:19:50,110 --> 00:19:52,270
I'm not sure if you know
French-- means blue,

356
00:19:52,270 --> 00:19:54,210
but rouge means red.

357
00:19:54,210 --> 00:20:00,650
So I guess they tried
to add some fun in this.

358
00:20:00,650 --> 00:20:02,450
But the problem
with these metrics

359
00:20:02,450 --> 00:20:06,850
is that you always
need a reference text.

360
00:20:06,850 --> 00:20:09,650
So you basically need labels.

361
00:20:09,650 --> 00:20:16,210
And in practice, having
labels is very cost expensive.

362
00:20:16,210 --> 00:20:21,650
It takes a lot of time, a
lot of money to get labels.

363
00:20:21,650 --> 00:20:24,220
And we will see
later in the class

364
00:20:24,220 --> 00:20:27,340
that with the progress that
we have made in the LLM space,

365
00:20:27,340 --> 00:20:30,740
or that the community has
made in the LLM space,

366
00:20:30,740 --> 00:20:36,020
we can actually forego of
this reference-based metrics

367
00:20:36,020 --> 00:20:40,400
and go towards a more
reference-free metrics.

368
00:20:40,400 --> 00:20:43,500
And we will see that later on.

369
00:20:43,500 --> 00:20:46,420
And then the last metric that I
will say that people sometimes

370
00:20:46,420 --> 00:20:48,780
use is called perplexity.

371
00:20:48,780 --> 00:20:52,580
And perplexity only looks
at the probabilities

372
00:20:52,580 --> 00:20:54,500
that are output by the model.

373
00:20:54,500 --> 00:20:58,940
And it basically
quantifies how surprised

374
00:20:58,940 --> 00:21:02,940
the model is by its output.

375
00:21:02,940 --> 00:21:06,060
So BLEU and ROUGE,
the higher the better.

376
00:21:06,060 --> 00:21:07,880
Perplexity, the
lower the better.

377
00:21:10,460 --> 00:21:19,020
And I guess LLMs have been
a hot topic since 2022.

378
00:21:19,020 --> 00:21:25,960
But actually, the field goes
way back, way before that year.

379
00:21:25,960 --> 00:21:29,460
So in the '80s, we'll
see it in a second,

380
00:21:29,460 --> 00:21:33,240
but there's a class of models
that were actually thought

381
00:21:33,240 --> 00:21:35,360
of, even in the '80s.

382
00:21:35,360 --> 00:21:41,280
And the '90s, we had LSTMs that
we'll see also in a second.

383
00:21:41,280 --> 00:21:43,640
But the problem was,
during that time,

384
00:21:43,640 --> 00:21:45,300
we didn't have the internet.

385
00:21:45,300 --> 00:21:47,560
We didn't have a lot of compute.

386
00:21:47,560 --> 00:21:50,280
And I guess this was one of
the limiting factors which

387
00:21:50,280 --> 00:21:56,960
prevented the models from
today from being trained.

388
00:21:56,960 --> 00:22:00,180
And then more recently,
we've had several advances.

389
00:22:00,180 --> 00:22:06,400
So Word2vec was really
one of the pioneering work

390
00:22:06,400 --> 00:22:11,000
in just computing
meaningful embeddings.

391
00:22:11,000 --> 00:22:12,300
And we'll see it in a second.

392
00:22:12,300 --> 00:22:14,980
And then, of course, we
had the transformers,

393
00:22:14,980 --> 00:22:19,960
which were part of a paper that
was published in 2017, which

394
00:22:19,960 --> 00:22:22,810
is basically at the foundation
of all of the models

395
00:22:22,810 --> 00:22:24,970
that you see today.

396
00:22:24,970 --> 00:22:31,410
And then these models, they just
were scaled up, both by compute,

397
00:22:31,410 --> 00:22:34,830
but also in terms of the data
that was used to train them.

398
00:22:34,830 --> 00:22:38,230
And that's how LLMs were dubbed.

399
00:22:38,230 --> 00:22:41,610
And I guess these are
more like the 2020s.

400
00:22:41,610 --> 00:22:43,430
But yeah, I guess
we'll see those.

401
00:22:46,330 --> 00:22:47,850
Cool.

402
00:22:47,850 --> 00:22:53,210
Any questions on, I
guess, the high level?

403
00:22:53,210 --> 00:22:55,690
Everyone good?

404
00:22:55,690 --> 00:22:56,830
Cool.

405
00:22:56,830 --> 00:23:01,450
So I guess the first
question that I

406
00:23:01,450 --> 00:23:05,370
want to ask ourselves
is, what we want to do

407
00:23:05,370 --> 00:23:08,490
is to have a model
that handles text.

408
00:23:08,490 --> 00:23:11,070
But models, they
understand numbers,

409
00:23:11,070 --> 00:23:13,130
they don't really
understand text.

410
00:23:13,130 --> 00:23:17,570
So we need to somehow do
something with that text

411
00:23:17,570 --> 00:23:20,750
to make it more
quantifiable, something

412
00:23:20,750 --> 00:23:23,390
that a model can understand.

413
00:23:23,390 --> 00:23:26,350
So if you look at a
sentence, for instance,

414
00:23:26,350 --> 00:23:31,910
"a cute teddy bear is reading,"
you first need to ask yourself,

415
00:23:31,910 --> 00:23:38,430
how can you cut this sentence
to pass it to a model?

416
00:23:38,430 --> 00:23:42,190
So this part is
called tokenization.

417
00:23:42,190 --> 00:23:45,070
And what that
entails is basically

418
00:23:45,070 --> 00:23:52,190
cutting the text with respect
to some arbitrary unit of text.

419
00:23:52,190 --> 00:23:54,710
So there are several
ways of doing this.

420
00:23:54,710 --> 00:23:58,950
I guess the first way is doing
it completely arbitrarily.

421
00:23:58,950 --> 00:24:00,710
So here, for instance,
you would have "a."

422
00:24:00,710 --> 00:24:03,630
That would be one unit of text.

423
00:24:03,630 --> 00:24:06,270
"Cute" could be
another unit of text.

424
00:24:06,270 --> 00:24:09,372
"Teddy bear" would be
another one, and so on.

425
00:24:09,372 --> 00:24:10,830
And by the way,
the unit of text is

426
00:24:10,830 --> 00:24:16,130
called a token, which is why the
method is called tokenization.

427
00:24:19,080 --> 00:24:22,030
Another way would be to
just separate by words.

428
00:24:25,240 --> 00:24:28,880
But I guess we would have
always pros and cons.

429
00:24:28,880 --> 00:24:33,800
I guess one of the goals
that we want to achieve

430
00:24:33,800 --> 00:24:38,200
is for us to then be able
to represent these tokens

431
00:24:38,200 --> 00:24:40,160
in a meaningful way.

432
00:24:40,160 --> 00:24:44,600
So one con with doing
this at the word level

433
00:24:44,600 --> 00:24:49,960
is you will end up with
words that look similar,

434
00:24:49,960 --> 00:24:53,320
but that are actually
considered as different tokens.

435
00:24:53,320 --> 00:24:56,640
And I guess the
limitation here is

436
00:24:56,640 --> 00:24:58,280
you will need to
compute embeddings

437
00:24:58,280 --> 00:25:02,560
for these similar
yet different tokens

438
00:25:02,560 --> 00:25:07,320
and somehow make their
embeddings similar.

439
00:25:07,320 --> 00:25:08,960
So I'll give you an example.

440
00:25:08,960 --> 00:25:12,600
So let's suppose I
have the word "bear."

441
00:25:12,600 --> 00:25:17,380
And then you have another
word, plural form "bears."

442
00:25:17,380 --> 00:25:20,240
So these two words,
they are very similar.

443
00:25:20,240 --> 00:25:23,020
Just one is singular,
the other one is plural.

444
00:25:23,020 --> 00:25:27,420
If we go ahead with the
word-level tokenization,

445
00:25:27,420 --> 00:25:32,340
then we will end up with
just two different entities,

446
00:25:32,340 --> 00:25:35,660
which are basically just
considered as different.

447
00:25:35,660 --> 00:25:42,420
Same with "run," and then
"runs," variations of verbs.

448
00:25:42,420 --> 00:25:49,180
So for that reason,
people have dug

449
00:25:49,180 --> 00:25:52,660
into a category
of tokenizers that

450
00:25:52,660 --> 00:25:58,620
are called subword tokenizers,
which is around leveraging roots

451
00:25:58,620 --> 00:26:03,660
of words in order to find what
are the common roots that we

452
00:26:03,660 --> 00:26:05,098
can find in these words.

453
00:26:05,098 --> 00:26:06,640
So, for instance,
for bear and bears,

454
00:26:06,640 --> 00:26:12,820
you would have the bear
particle that would be shared.

455
00:26:12,820 --> 00:26:17,070
And so I guess the pro is
that you get to leverage

456
00:26:17,070 --> 00:26:18,910
the root of the words.

457
00:26:18,910 --> 00:26:24,870
But then the con here is that
your sequence would be longer.

458
00:26:24,870 --> 00:26:28,990
And we will see
why this is a con.

459
00:26:28,990 --> 00:26:33,390
I guess later on, I guess
I can give you a preview.

460
00:26:33,390 --> 00:26:36,750
So the complexity
of these models

461
00:26:36,750 --> 00:26:40,830
is also a function of
the sequence length.

462
00:26:40,830 --> 00:26:44,630
So the more tokens
you have to process,

463
00:26:44,630 --> 00:26:47,910
the more time it will take
for your model to run,

464
00:26:47,910 --> 00:26:52,350
because it needs to basically
process all these tokens.

465
00:26:52,350 --> 00:26:53,450
So that's one con.

466
00:26:53,450 --> 00:26:57,470
So pro is it leverages
the root of words.

467
00:26:57,470 --> 00:27:02,340
Con is it just makes
your sequences longer.

468
00:27:05,630 --> 00:27:09,830
You have a last category of
ways of tokenizing things, which

469
00:27:09,830 --> 00:27:11,810
is just going at
the character level,

470
00:27:11,810 --> 00:27:13,850
just like taking out characters.

471
00:27:13,850 --> 00:27:20,610
So here, I guess, you and
I when we write a message,

472
00:27:20,610 --> 00:27:24,370
we typically have
sometimes misspellings.

473
00:27:24,370 --> 00:27:29,610
And with the subword way
of tokenizing things,

474
00:27:29,610 --> 00:27:34,250
you may not be able to
recognize the word that

475
00:27:34,250 --> 00:27:36,490
has been misspelled.

476
00:27:36,490 --> 00:27:39,050
And this is something that
the character-level tokenizer

477
00:27:39,050 --> 00:27:43,130
can, I guess, take
into consideration.

478
00:27:43,130 --> 00:27:47,090
But here the problem is you
have a sequence length that's

479
00:27:47,090 --> 00:27:50,350
much, much longer, which
will make your model,

480
00:27:50,350 --> 00:27:54,250
I guess, take much more time
to process the sequence.

481
00:27:54,250 --> 00:27:55,730
So that's one con.

482
00:27:55,730 --> 00:27:59,090
And then the other
con is, I guess,

483
00:27:59,090 --> 00:28:01,870
when you want to represent
each of these tokens,

484
00:28:01,870 --> 00:28:06,330
I guess it's very hard to
know that a representation

485
00:28:06,330 --> 00:28:08,560
of a letter really means.

486
00:28:08,560 --> 00:28:12,740
Like, what does the
representation of the letter U

487
00:28:12,740 --> 00:28:14,460
mean.

488
00:28:14,460 --> 00:28:17,820
It's very hard.

489
00:28:17,820 --> 00:28:18,440
OK, cool.

490
00:28:18,440 --> 00:28:21,620
So I have just a quick recap.

491
00:28:21,620 --> 00:28:27,260
So word-level is a super naive
way, super simple way of,

492
00:28:27,260 --> 00:28:32,500
I guess, dividing your
text into arbitrary units.

493
00:28:32,500 --> 00:28:34,620
But then the problem
is, as we mentioned,

494
00:28:34,620 --> 00:28:37,700
we do not leverage
the root of words.

495
00:28:37,700 --> 00:28:41,540
And I did not mention
this, but there is a term.

496
00:28:41,540 --> 00:28:47,860
Whenever you cut something
and then at inference time

497
00:28:47,860 --> 00:28:50,020
when you want to
make a prediction,

498
00:28:50,020 --> 00:28:54,060
I guess, one prerequisite
that you have is

499
00:28:54,060 --> 00:28:58,700
that you need to have the token
that you saw at training time,

500
00:28:58,700 --> 00:29:02,060
you need to have it
in your training sets.

501
00:29:02,060 --> 00:29:06,700
And the problem is, let's
suppose at inference time

502
00:29:06,700 --> 00:29:09,230
you cut your text into words.

503
00:29:09,230 --> 00:29:12,670
And let's suppose you have not
seen a word at training time.

504
00:29:12,670 --> 00:29:16,710
You will need to
mark it as unknown.

505
00:29:16,710 --> 00:29:21,350
And so this thing is called
OOV, Out Of Vocabulary.

506
00:29:21,350 --> 00:29:24,230
So luckily, the
subword-level tokenizer

507
00:29:24,230 --> 00:29:26,630
mitigates that problem.

508
00:29:26,630 --> 00:29:33,910
So you have a lower risk of
OOV, but still you can have.

509
00:29:33,910 --> 00:29:36,390
And as we mentioned,
in terms of the pro,

510
00:29:36,390 --> 00:29:39,040
you leverage the
roots of the words.

511
00:29:41,830 --> 00:29:46,430
And then character-level, it's
robust to our misspellings

512
00:29:46,430 --> 00:29:48,790
and our casing errors.

513
00:29:48,790 --> 00:29:52,950
But the problem is it makes
computations just much slower.

514
00:29:52,950 --> 00:29:57,670
And your sequences would
be very, very long,

515
00:29:57,670 --> 00:29:59,690
which will also
make your, I guess,

516
00:29:59,690 --> 00:30:03,510
inference time much higher.

517
00:30:03,510 --> 00:30:04,410
That sound good?

518
00:30:04,410 --> 00:30:07,138
I guess this is really
the foundation, I guess,

519
00:30:07,138 --> 00:30:08,430
how to handle things with text.

520
00:30:08,430 --> 00:30:10,055
But yeah, does that
make sense overall?

521
00:30:13,290 --> 00:30:15,090
Cool.

522
00:30:15,090 --> 00:30:21,410
OK, so now what we did
is we took an input text.

523
00:30:21,410 --> 00:30:26,930
What we did is we cut it into
parts that are basically tokens.

524
00:30:26,930 --> 00:30:30,490
So in order for our model
to understand these tokens,

525
00:30:30,490 --> 00:30:34,690
we need to find a
representation for each of them.

526
00:30:34,690 --> 00:30:37,545
So here, we're going
to take a look at this.

527
00:30:37,545 --> 00:30:39,170
So that's called a
word representation.

528
00:30:39,170 --> 00:30:43,610
Or I guess, in a
more correct way,

529
00:30:43,610 --> 00:30:45,630
it should be token
representation.

530
00:30:45,630 --> 00:30:49,900
So we want to find a way to
represent each of these tokens.

531
00:30:52,530 --> 00:30:54,810
So the simple and
naive way to do this

532
00:30:54,810 --> 00:31:01,730
would be to just assign the
one hot vector for each word

533
00:31:01,730 --> 00:31:03,250
or for each token.

534
00:31:03,250 --> 00:31:06,460
So for instance,
let's suppose we have

535
00:31:06,460 --> 00:31:09,540
a vocabulary of three tokens--

536
00:31:09,540 --> 00:31:12,620
book, soft, and teddy bears.

537
00:31:12,620 --> 00:31:14,320
We would have, let's say, soft.

538
00:31:14,320 --> 00:31:16,900
That is 1, 0, 0 vector.

539
00:31:16,900 --> 00:31:20,500
Teddy bear, that is, let's
say a 0, 1, 0 vector.

540
00:31:20,500 --> 00:31:25,380
And book, that is, let's
say, a 0, 0, 1 vector.

541
00:31:25,380 --> 00:31:30,100
So this is called a
One-Hot Encoding, OHE.

542
00:31:30,100 --> 00:31:32,980
We'll typically see.

543
00:31:32,980 --> 00:31:33,660
So cool.

544
00:31:33,660 --> 00:31:37,440
This is a way to
represent our tokens.

545
00:31:37,440 --> 00:31:40,660
But basically what
people want to do

546
00:31:40,660 --> 00:31:44,220
is compare these
tokens to basically see

547
00:31:44,220 --> 00:31:50,060
which ones are more
similar to what other ones.

548
00:31:50,060 --> 00:31:53,620
So common similarity
measure that people use

549
00:31:53,620 --> 00:31:56,920
is something called
cosine similarity.

550
00:31:56,920 --> 00:31:59,700
I'm not sure if you
have heard of it.

551
00:31:59,700 --> 00:32:02,660
So you can think of
it as just seeing

552
00:32:02,660 --> 00:32:09,200
what angle these vectors make
in the n dimensional space.

553
00:32:09,200 --> 00:32:14,300
And if, I guess, they are
pointing in the same direction,

554
00:32:14,300 --> 00:32:16,020
then maybe they're similar.

555
00:32:16,020 --> 00:32:19,980
Maybe if they're orthogonal,
maybe they're independent.

556
00:32:19,980 --> 00:32:22,102
And if they're
completely opposite, then

557
00:32:22,102 --> 00:32:23,060
maybe they're opposite.

558
00:32:23,060 --> 00:32:28,640
That's basically the mental
model we want to go into.

559
00:32:28,640 --> 00:32:33,560
So the problem is, if you
represent your tokens in a one

560
00:32:33,560 --> 00:32:37,680
hot fashion, you will end
up with all your vectors

561
00:32:37,680 --> 00:32:41,720
being orthogonal to one another.

562
00:32:41,720 --> 00:32:43,560
So that's the problem.

563
00:32:43,560 --> 00:32:47,720
So ideally, what we
want is for tokens

564
00:32:47,720 --> 00:32:52,160
that mean the same or
similar to basically have

565
00:32:52,160 --> 00:32:54,680
a high similarity.

566
00:32:54,680 --> 00:32:59,680
And for tokens that are
not similar on about

567
00:32:59,680 --> 00:33:03,850
different thing, to
be more orthogonal.

568
00:33:03,850 --> 00:33:09,530
So here, just for illustrative
purposes, teddy bears are soft.

569
00:33:09,530 --> 00:33:12,730
So you want teddy bear
and soft to be, I guess,

570
00:33:12,730 --> 00:33:14,370
with a high similarity.

571
00:33:14,370 --> 00:33:17,350
And let's say teddy bear and
book, which is independent,

572
00:33:17,350 --> 00:33:21,050
you want them to be closer to 0.

573
00:33:21,050 --> 00:33:22,850
So that's what you want.

574
00:33:22,850 --> 00:33:24,690
That's what you have
with one-hot encoding,

575
00:33:24,690 --> 00:33:27,630
and that's what you want.

576
00:33:27,630 --> 00:33:28,130
Yeah.

577
00:33:31,740 --> 00:33:32,240
Sorry?

578
00:33:38,610 --> 00:33:39,930
Oh, I see.

579
00:33:39,930 --> 00:33:44,090
The question is, why do
you care about the norm?

580
00:33:44,090 --> 00:33:50,810
So I guess cosine similarity is
actually normalized by norms.

581
00:33:50,810 --> 00:33:53,270
So it's dot products.

582
00:33:53,270 --> 00:33:56,590
Oh, you mean why did I just put
dot product here instead of 2?

583
00:34:01,310 --> 00:34:01,890
Oh, I see.

584
00:34:01,890 --> 00:34:06,150
And your question is, why do
we not care about the norm?

585
00:34:06,150 --> 00:34:08,590
Cool, I guess the viewers
know the question.

586
00:34:08,590 --> 00:34:12,230
I guess these measures,
they are all measures.

587
00:34:12,230 --> 00:34:20,310
They are all ways to try to
capture these similarity things.

588
00:34:20,310 --> 00:34:22,759
So I guess why do you
not care about the norm?

589
00:34:25,389 --> 00:34:29,550
I guess it's how people
have tried to quantify that.

590
00:34:29,550 --> 00:34:34,070
I guess you will need to see
how your vectors are trained

591
00:34:34,070 --> 00:34:39,469
and whether the norm would
be indicative of something.

592
00:34:39,469 --> 00:34:41,949
I guess the best answer I
can give you is, I guess,

593
00:34:41,949 --> 00:34:42,850
this is a measure.

594
00:34:42,850 --> 00:34:46,090
This is not the perfect measure.

595
00:34:46,090 --> 00:34:49,250
People may use also dot
product as a measure,

596
00:34:49,250 --> 00:34:53,710
but yeah, I don't have
a great answer for you.

597
00:34:53,710 --> 00:34:55,510
But as long as you
capture, I guess,

598
00:34:55,510 --> 00:34:59,660
how these vectors
they're pointing,

599
00:34:59,660 --> 00:35:03,880
I guess, typically what you care
about is the angle between them.

600
00:35:03,880 --> 00:35:05,640
But typically, you
don't really take

601
00:35:05,640 --> 00:35:07,500
into consideration the norm.

602
00:35:10,240 --> 00:35:11,420
Cool, any questions?

603
00:35:11,420 --> 00:35:13,600
Any other questions?

604
00:35:13,600 --> 00:35:29,580
Yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah.

605
00:35:39,423 --> 00:35:40,340
It's a great question.

606
00:35:40,340 --> 00:35:43,520
So the question is
around size of vocabulary

607
00:35:43,520 --> 00:35:45,760
and how that would inform
the choice with respect

608
00:35:45,760 --> 00:35:48,860
to word, subword, and how
that changes across languages.

609
00:35:48,860 --> 00:35:50,535
So great question.

610
00:35:50,535 --> 00:35:52,160
So I would say it
really depends, first

611
00:35:52,160 --> 00:35:54,760
of all, on the tasks that
you're trying to achieve.

612
00:35:54,760 --> 00:35:57,200
If your task is just
about one language,

613
00:35:57,200 --> 00:35:59,940
you will just take
that same language.

614
00:35:59,940 --> 00:36:04,020
You would typically go with a
subword tokenizer just because

615
00:36:04,020 --> 00:36:07,500
of the reasons that
we mentioned here.

616
00:36:07,500 --> 00:36:11,940
So I guess subwords is a
nice trade-off between being

617
00:36:11,940 --> 00:36:16,180
able to identify
words by their roots,

618
00:36:16,180 --> 00:36:20,830
like leveraging that, but also
running less into the OOV risk.

619
00:36:23,860 --> 00:36:28,140
So in terms of the
size, I know that people

620
00:36:28,140 --> 00:36:31,920
have tried different things.

621
00:36:31,920 --> 00:36:33,940
I think typically
for English, you

622
00:36:33,940 --> 00:36:37,500
would target something on the
order of tens of thousands

623
00:36:37,500 --> 00:36:40,020
of vocabulary size.

624
00:36:40,020 --> 00:36:44,840
But nowadays, the models,
they are multilingual,

625
00:36:44,840 --> 00:36:46,460
they are also about codes.

626
00:36:46,460 --> 00:36:48,340
So you will see that
the vocabulary size now

627
00:36:48,340 --> 00:36:52,900
is sometimes on the order
of hundreds of thousands.

628
00:36:52,900 --> 00:36:55,310
So with respect to
Chinese, so I guess

629
00:36:55,310 --> 00:37:00,050
you have this difference in
characters that you're using.

630
00:37:00,050 --> 00:37:02,790
So for Latin, I guess
it's the alphabet

631
00:37:02,790 --> 00:37:03,970
we're all accustomed to.

632
00:37:03,970 --> 00:37:06,390
But of course for
the other ones,

633
00:37:06,390 --> 00:37:08,790
you'd have something
similar, but in I

634
00:37:08,790 --> 00:37:13,990
guess the target
language character.

635
00:37:13,990 --> 00:37:17,750
So yeah, I would say order of
magnitude, tens of thousands

636
00:37:17,750 --> 00:37:22,950
for one language, hundreds of
thousands if it's multilingual.

637
00:37:22,950 --> 00:37:25,530
These are the order of magnitude
that you want to target for.

638
00:37:28,150 --> 00:37:29,610
Cool, yeah.

639
00:37:41,230 --> 00:37:41,890
Great question.

640
00:37:41,890 --> 00:37:44,057
So the question is, how do
you get those embeddings?

641
00:37:44,057 --> 00:37:45,590
So it's actually the next slide.

642
00:37:45,590 --> 00:37:49,030
So I'm going to talk about this.

643
00:37:49,030 --> 00:37:52,913
Cool, great.

644
00:37:52,913 --> 00:37:58,400
So now that we know that
the one-hot encoding is not

645
00:37:58,400 --> 00:38:01,520
a good way to represent
tokens, what we want to do

646
00:38:01,520 --> 00:38:06,800
is to learn those
embeddings from the data.

647
00:38:06,800 --> 00:38:11,320
So I mentioned that there
was this paper that came out

648
00:38:11,320 --> 00:38:15,960
in the 2010s-- so I think it was
2013-- that was called Word2vec.

649
00:38:15,960 --> 00:38:19,040
And the reason why
it was so popular

650
00:38:19,040 --> 00:38:25,080
is because they showed a very
intuitive and interpretable way

651
00:38:25,080 --> 00:38:28,360
of seeing these embeddings,
because they were saying

652
00:38:28,360 --> 00:38:31,320
something like, OK, king is to
queen, what this is to that,

653
00:38:31,320 --> 00:38:33,860
like Paris is to France
what Berlin is to Germany.

654
00:38:33,860 --> 00:38:39,760
So there was basically a way to
make sense of the embeddings.

655
00:38:39,760 --> 00:38:43,120
So now the question is,
how did they do that?

656
00:38:43,120 --> 00:38:47,700
So they had two ways of
computing these embeddings.

657
00:38:47,700 --> 00:38:51,100
So one way was called
continuous bag of words.

658
00:38:51,100 --> 00:38:53,100
The other one was
called skip gram.

659
00:38:53,100 --> 00:38:56,260
But they all rely
on the same idea,

660
00:38:56,260 --> 00:39:03,500
which is let's just leverage
texts that we have, and then try

661
00:39:03,500 --> 00:39:07,220
to predict something
that is part of the text,

662
00:39:07,220 --> 00:39:10,060
based on, let's
say, the context.

663
00:39:10,060 --> 00:39:14,100
So for instance, continuous
bag of words, the goal

664
00:39:14,100 --> 00:39:17,700
is you take into consideration
the words that are

665
00:39:17,700 --> 00:39:20,980
around a given target words.

666
00:39:20,980 --> 00:39:25,500
And your goal is to
predict that target word.

667
00:39:25,500 --> 00:39:27,540
And skip gram is the opposite.

668
00:39:27,540 --> 00:39:30,700
You go from a
target word and you

669
00:39:30,700 --> 00:39:34,540
want to predict the
words that are around it.

670
00:39:34,540 --> 00:39:39,660
So I guess this task is
commonly called a proxy task.

671
00:39:39,660 --> 00:39:43,260
Because at the end of the
day, in this exercise,

672
00:39:43,260 --> 00:39:45,540
what we care about
is not necessarily

673
00:39:45,540 --> 00:39:49,750
to predict the next word,
or at least not yet.

674
00:39:49,750 --> 00:39:53,910
Our goal is to learn a
representation of these words

675
00:39:53,910 --> 00:39:56,310
that are meaningful.

676
00:39:56,310 --> 00:40:03,270
And so here the idea is, if you
have a model that somehow knows

677
00:40:03,270 --> 00:40:07,830
how to predict, let's say,
the next word, then it

678
00:40:07,830 --> 00:40:13,390
means that your model has some
understanding of how language

679
00:40:13,390 --> 00:40:16,890
works, which is
basically what you want.

680
00:40:16,890 --> 00:40:21,030
You basically want an
embedding that is reflective

681
00:40:21,030 --> 00:40:27,910
of, I guess, what language
is, which is king and queen,

682
00:40:27,910 --> 00:40:32,070
or similar, Paris and
France, this is a capital.

683
00:40:32,070 --> 00:40:35,150
You want to have these
associations embedded

684
00:40:35,150 --> 00:40:36,490
in the representation.

685
00:40:39,710 --> 00:40:43,630
And let's go through
a very simple example

686
00:40:43,630 --> 00:40:47,110
of what that looks like.

687
00:40:47,110 --> 00:40:53,010
So here in our example, let's
suppose that our proxy task is

688
00:40:53,010 --> 00:40:56,330
about predicting the next word.

689
00:40:56,330 --> 00:41:01,370
So here what we take is
a very vanilla neural

690
00:41:01,370 --> 00:41:09,610
network model, which basically
receives a vector of size v,

691
00:41:09,610 --> 00:41:12,850
has multiplication
and a bias term

692
00:41:12,850 --> 00:41:19,930
to get a hidden state, and then
another set of multiplications

693
00:41:19,930 --> 00:41:23,610
to get our final vector.

694
00:41:23,610 --> 00:41:28,890
So here it's basically a
very simple neural network.

695
00:41:28,890 --> 00:41:33,810
So the input is of size v.
The hidden layer is of size

696
00:41:33,810 --> 00:41:37,088
d, which is typically much
smaller than the vocabulary.

697
00:41:37,088 --> 00:41:39,130
So vocabulary is typically
like tens of thousands

698
00:41:39,130 --> 00:41:40,590
or hundreds of thousands.

699
00:41:40,590 --> 00:41:43,850
So d is typically hundred.

700
00:41:43,850 --> 00:41:50,260
Like, 768, for instance, is
one example of dimension.

701
00:41:50,260 --> 00:41:52,580
So it's much, much smaller.

702
00:41:52,580 --> 00:41:57,740
So what we're trying to do is
to learn the word representation

703
00:41:57,740 --> 00:41:59,200
through this proxy task.

704
00:41:59,200 --> 00:42:02,660
And what we're
going to do is try

705
00:42:02,660 --> 00:42:09,890
to consider the words as inputs
and predict the next word.

706
00:42:12,700 --> 00:42:16,440
So let's go with the first
word of the sequence.

707
00:42:16,440 --> 00:42:21,500
So by the way, I use token
and words interchangeably.

708
00:42:21,500 --> 00:42:25,580
So let's suppose we have the
word "a," and we want to predict

709
00:42:25,580 --> 00:42:29,260
the next word, which
is the word "cute."

710
00:42:29,260 --> 00:42:37,100
So what we do is we take the
word "a," we take the one-hot

711
00:42:37,100 --> 00:42:42,500
encoding representation, and
we pass it through the network.

712
00:42:42,500 --> 00:42:45,180
So here, if you're familiar
with neural networks,

713
00:42:45,180 --> 00:42:47,960
so here you have, I
guess, a multiplication

714
00:42:47,960 --> 00:42:51,040
between a matrix
and this vector.

715
00:42:51,040 --> 00:42:54,680
So you have a hidden
state representation,

716
00:42:54,680 --> 00:42:58,200
which is a vector of size d.

717
00:42:58,200 --> 00:43:04,120
So here, let's suppose it's
0.2 and 0.9, so D equal 2.

718
00:43:04,120 --> 00:43:07,600
And then you have, I
guess, another pass here.

719
00:43:07,600 --> 00:43:10,480
And then you get,
after softmax, a set

720
00:43:10,480 --> 00:43:14,680
of probabilities
which are around

721
00:43:14,680 --> 00:43:17,640
seeing what is the next word.

722
00:43:17,640 --> 00:43:24,480
So in this example, we have
a vocabulary of size 6.

723
00:43:24,480 --> 00:43:27,840
So the first word is
predicted with probability

724
00:43:27,840 --> 00:43:33,320
0.2, second word, 0.4,
and then the other words

725
00:43:33,320 --> 00:43:36,480
are all 0.1 in this example.

726
00:43:36,480 --> 00:43:41,320
So let's suppose that
we want to somehow

727
00:43:41,320 --> 00:43:44,530
be able to maximize
our prediction

728
00:43:44,530 --> 00:43:49,570
to be the second word of the
vocabulary, which is the 0.4.

729
00:43:49,570 --> 00:43:54,930
So we basically compare the
prediction with, I guess,

730
00:43:54,930 --> 00:43:58,010
0, 1, 0, 0, 0, which
is the representation

731
00:43:58,010 --> 00:44:01,930
of the second word
of the vocabulary.

732
00:44:01,930 --> 00:44:06,530
And then we do the back
prop, we update the weights.

733
00:44:06,530 --> 00:44:09,610
I'm not sure if everyone
is familiar with that part.

734
00:44:09,610 --> 00:44:14,870
But the idea here is, once
you obtain a prediction,

735
00:44:14,870 --> 00:44:19,130
you compute the loss, so
typically cross-entropy,

736
00:44:19,130 --> 00:44:25,170
which will determine how far off
you are from the true answer.

737
00:44:25,170 --> 00:44:27,650
And based on that
difference, you're

738
00:44:27,650 --> 00:44:30,610
going to update the
weights in order

739
00:44:30,610 --> 00:44:36,690
to make your prediction
closer to the truth.

740
00:44:36,690 --> 00:44:37,890
So that's what you do.

741
00:44:37,890 --> 00:44:39,270
And then you repeat
that process.

742
00:44:39,270 --> 00:44:43,610
Let's suppose you take the
word "cute," which, as we said,

743
00:44:43,610 --> 00:44:45,770
is the second word
in the vocabulary.

744
00:44:45,770 --> 00:44:51,670
So the one-hot encoding
representation is 0, 1, 0, 0, 0.

745
00:44:51,670 --> 00:44:58,230
So you go through that network,
you have a hidden state,

746
00:44:58,230 --> 00:45:00,210
like the vector is 0.8 and 0.4.

747
00:45:00,210 --> 00:45:01,350
You do that again.

748
00:45:01,350 --> 00:45:04,610
And what you want to do is
to predict the next token,

749
00:45:04,610 --> 00:45:08,150
and here is teddy bear.

750
00:45:08,150 --> 00:45:11,390
And so you see now your
model in this example

751
00:45:11,390 --> 00:45:14,730
is predicting the next
word to be uniform,

752
00:45:14,730 --> 00:45:19,310
but you want to somehow maximize
the probability for teddy bear.

753
00:45:19,310 --> 00:45:23,350
So you go about doing this again
and again for all the words.

754
00:45:23,350 --> 00:45:28,110
And at the end of the
day, you obtain a model

755
00:45:28,110 --> 00:45:33,190
that learns how to predict the
next word, which is basically

756
00:45:33,190 --> 00:45:34,790
the proxy task.

757
00:45:34,790 --> 00:45:38,590
And what you're going to do
is to take the representation

758
00:45:38,590 --> 00:45:43,840
that the model learns,
which is the green units.

759
00:45:43,840 --> 00:45:47,840
So what happens now is
every time you have a word,

760
00:45:47,840 --> 00:45:54,240
you just represent that as a
one-hot encoding representation.

761
00:45:54,240 --> 00:45:57,720
And you just multiply
this with these weights,

762
00:45:57,720 --> 00:46:02,160
and then you obtain the
green representation.

763
00:46:02,160 --> 00:46:05,728
And that is your
word representation.

764
00:46:09,480 --> 00:46:10,460
Does that make sense?

765
00:46:10,460 --> 00:46:28,560
Yeah, yeah.

766
00:46:33,800 --> 00:46:36,460
Yeah, great question,
great question.

767
00:46:36,460 --> 00:46:38,650
So the question is about
what does v correspond to

768
00:46:38,650 --> 00:46:39,790
and why there's only six.

769
00:46:39,790 --> 00:46:44,370
So yes, in this example we only
have six possible words, which

770
00:46:44,370 --> 00:46:48,930
is basically the vocabulary
size, just like a very toy

771
00:46:48,930 --> 00:46:53,050
example, because in
practice there is many more.

772
00:46:53,050 --> 00:46:57,430
So I guess that's one of the
challenges with language.

773
00:46:57,430 --> 00:46:59,770
So you can technically
have many variations

774
00:46:59,770 --> 00:47:05,090
of words, which is why if
you take a word-level way

775
00:47:05,090 --> 00:47:08,050
to divide your text into
tokens, you can end up

776
00:47:08,050 --> 00:47:10,630
with the vocabulary
that's very big,

777
00:47:10,630 --> 00:47:13,290
because you need to account
for all the variations of given

778
00:47:13,290 --> 00:47:15,570
words.

779
00:47:15,570 --> 00:47:17,730
And the other thing
that I want to point out

780
00:47:17,730 --> 00:47:22,742
is, let's suppose you have
a vocabulary size of 6,

781
00:47:22,742 --> 00:47:24,950
and it's the six words that
you saw at training time.

782
00:47:24,950 --> 00:47:27,030
But what happens if
at inference time

783
00:47:27,030 --> 00:47:31,410
you have a word that you have
not seen at training time?

784
00:47:31,410 --> 00:47:34,250
And so the answer for that
is typically what people do

785
00:47:34,250 --> 00:47:39,710
is they reserve a
spot for what they

786
00:47:39,710 --> 00:47:44,230
call an unknown token or
out-of-vocabulary token,

787
00:47:44,230 --> 00:47:50,510
which is basically you can think
of it as a bucket for everything

788
00:47:50,510 --> 00:47:55,150
that we were not
able to identify.

789
00:47:55,150 --> 00:47:57,150
So if let's suppose
at inference time

790
00:47:57,150 --> 00:48:00,990
you have a token that you
were not able to identify,

791
00:48:00,990 --> 00:48:03,010
they will all take
that representation,

792
00:48:03,010 --> 00:48:06,893
which is the unknown
token representation.

793
00:48:06,893 --> 00:48:08,310
And this is, by
the way, something

794
00:48:08,310 --> 00:48:15,710
that I guess the word-level
tokenizer has trouble to do,

795
00:48:15,710 --> 00:48:18,750
because you will have a
much bigger chance of having

796
00:48:18,750 --> 00:48:21,590
out-of-vocabulary tokens.

797
00:48:21,590 --> 00:48:23,750
Subword level will
have a lower chance.

798
00:48:23,750 --> 00:48:26,530
And then character
level, I guess,

799
00:48:26,530 --> 00:48:28,350
you don't have that problem.

800
00:48:28,350 --> 00:48:30,050
Does that answer your question?

801
00:48:30,050 --> 00:48:31,110
Yeah.

802
00:48:31,110 --> 00:48:34,160
Cool, yeah.

803
00:48:53,383 --> 00:48:54,300
Great, great question.

804
00:48:54,300 --> 00:48:57,760
So first question
is, when you're done?

805
00:48:57,760 --> 00:49:01,720
So the thing with the proxy task
is when you train your model,

806
00:49:01,720 --> 00:49:05,780
I guess your true objective
is to not really learn--

807
00:49:05,780 --> 00:49:06,800
I mean, in this case--

808
00:49:06,800 --> 00:49:08,420
to learn how to
predict the next word.

809
00:49:08,420 --> 00:49:11,560
Your objective is to have
meaningful representations.

810
00:49:11,560 --> 00:49:15,120
But what you can do
is to somehow track

811
00:49:15,120 --> 00:49:18,920
the loss function for the proxy
task that you're pursuing,

812
00:49:18,920 --> 00:49:21,760
but then also taking into
consideration that this is not

813
00:49:21,760 --> 00:49:24,000
necessarily your end goal.

814
00:49:24,000 --> 00:49:28,120
So I guess one
very reasonable way

815
00:49:28,120 --> 00:49:31,340
of going about doing this is
just to wait until your model

816
00:49:31,340 --> 00:49:32,260
converges.

817
00:49:32,260 --> 00:49:35,860
So here, what you do
is you track the loss

818
00:49:35,860 --> 00:49:37,420
as a function of--

819
00:49:37,420 --> 00:49:40,500
so there's this term "epoch,"
just how many times your model

820
00:49:40,500 --> 00:49:42,620
sees the training set.

821
00:49:42,620 --> 00:49:45,400
And so you compare
these different curves.

822
00:49:45,400 --> 00:49:49,060
And when this converges,
this is typically a good time

823
00:49:49,060 --> 00:49:54,040
to stop the training process and
just see if that makes sense.

824
00:49:54,040 --> 00:49:57,380
Depends on your downstream
task, of course.

825
00:49:57,380 --> 00:49:59,700
But that's one.

826
00:49:59,700 --> 00:50:01,380
So your second
question-- sorry, can you

827
00:50:01,380 --> 00:50:04,380
repeat the second question?

828
00:50:04,380 --> 00:50:18,200
Yeah, yeah, oh, great question.

829
00:50:18,200 --> 00:50:23,720
So the question is, how do you
know when the generation stops?

830
00:50:23,720 --> 00:50:26,740
I guess, otherwise
it will never stop.

831
00:50:26,740 --> 00:50:27,460
So yeah, exactly.

832
00:50:27,460 --> 00:50:29,420
So you have some special tokens.

833
00:50:29,420 --> 00:50:33,330
Typically, you have end of
sequence, end of sequence.

834
00:50:33,330 --> 00:50:36,210
So typically when you have the
end of sequence token generated,

835
00:50:36,210 --> 00:50:37,520
then it's when it stops.

836
00:50:40,310 --> 00:50:41,010
All right.

837
00:50:41,010 --> 00:50:45,070
So second question
was what informs

838
00:50:45,070 --> 00:50:48,030
the size of the hidden layer?

839
00:50:48,030 --> 00:50:52,310
I would say it's a
trade-off, because you

840
00:50:52,310 --> 00:50:55,790
want the embedding
to be rich enough

841
00:50:55,790 --> 00:50:59,550
that it can be informative
for your downstream task.

842
00:50:59,550 --> 00:51:02,030
So for instance, if
you want to somehow get

843
00:51:02,030 --> 00:51:04,990
an embedding of, let's
say, your sentence,

844
00:51:04,990 --> 00:51:07,150
and if you want to, let's
say, do a very, very

845
00:51:07,150 --> 00:51:11,690
specialized task, like with
a lot of different outcomes,

846
00:51:11,690 --> 00:51:14,950
maybe you want a vector that
recaptures that, so maybe you

847
00:51:14,950 --> 00:51:18,690
want a bigger vector, but if
you had a very simple task,

848
00:51:18,690 --> 00:51:22,030
maybe a smaller vector
might make sense.

849
00:51:22,030 --> 00:51:26,630
So I guess the size of
your hidden dimension

850
00:51:26,630 --> 00:51:31,570
also impacts the complexity of
whatever you're running after.

851
00:51:31,570 --> 00:51:34,190
Because of course, if
you have longer vectors,

852
00:51:34,190 --> 00:51:37,810
you'll have more computation, so
your inference will be probably

853
00:51:37,810 --> 00:51:39,870
more expensive, et cetera.

854
00:51:39,870 --> 00:51:42,130
So I guess there's
a lot of factors.

855
00:51:42,130 --> 00:51:44,810
So I guess just to recap,
one is how complicated

856
00:51:44,810 --> 00:51:46,930
your downstream task is.

857
00:51:46,930 --> 00:51:49,970
Second one is how
sensitive are you

858
00:51:49,970 --> 00:51:52,770
with latency, cost,
all these things.

859
00:51:52,770 --> 00:51:54,250
So it's really a trade-off.

860
00:51:54,250 --> 00:51:55,970
But out there you
would typically

861
00:51:55,970 --> 00:52:02,090
see embeddings of a pool
of hundreds or thousands.

862
00:52:02,090 --> 00:52:04,430
Of course, these models,
they've been growing,

863
00:52:04,430 --> 00:52:06,110
so this number may change.

864
00:52:06,110 --> 00:52:07,730
But that's the
order of magnitude

865
00:52:07,730 --> 00:52:08,710
that you're looking at.

866
00:52:11,850 --> 00:52:12,998
Right.

867
00:52:12,998 --> 00:52:14,040
This is indeed empirical.

868
00:52:14,040 --> 00:52:15,050
Yeah, yeah.

869
00:52:15,050 --> 00:52:17,970
I guess you can also
rely on what others found

870
00:52:17,970 --> 00:52:19,210
and just go from that.

871
00:52:19,210 --> 00:52:23,070
But 768, these numbers are
things that people typically

872
00:52:23,070 --> 00:52:23,570
take.

873
00:52:27,260 --> 00:52:29,780
Cool, yeah.

874
00:52:47,335 --> 00:52:47,960
Great question.

875
00:52:47,960 --> 00:52:52,180
So the question is,
how can you distinguish

876
00:52:52,180 --> 00:52:55,460
words that are spelled the
same but in different contexts?

877
00:52:55,460 --> 00:52:57,220
So you're way ahead of me.

878
00:52:57,220 --> 00:52:59,420
So this is basically the basics.

879
00:52:59,420 --> 00:53:02,100
And we're going
to tackle methods

880
00:53:02,100 --> 00:53:05,580
that can tackle these problems
of just contextualizing

881
00:53:05,580 --> 00:53:08,100
the word in the sentence.

882
00:53:08,100 --> 00:53:10,560
So yeah, so we'll
see that in a bit.

883
00:53:14,360 --> 00:53:14,860
Cool.

884
00:53:17,924 --> 00:53:19,080
I'm not on time.

885
00:53:19,080 --> 00:53:21,980
So I'll try to get moving.

886
00:53:21,980 --> 00:53:25,920
So OK, so now what
we did was see

887
00:53:25,920 --> 00:53:31,080
how we could learn
representations of tokens.

888
00:53:31,080 --> 00:53:36,440
But I guess you may also
want to get representations

889
00:53:36,440 --> 00:53:41,120
of sentences or pieces of text.

890
00:53:41,120 --> 00:53:46,920
So one very naive way to do
that with what we saw before

891
00:53:46,920 --> 00:53:50,840
is to take something like
the average of words,

892
00:53:50,840 --> 00:53:53,240
let's say, the word
representations.

893
00:53:53,240 --> 00:53:56,140
But the problem is you
lose a lot of meaning,

894
00:53:56,140 --> 00:53:59,600
you lose the order, you lose--

895
00:53:59,600 --> 00:54:02,600
and I guess here, I think
you pointed out very well,

896
00:54:02,600 --> 00:54:04,360
the representations
that you learn

897
00:54:04,360 --> 00:54:09,720
are token-specific, regardless
of where they're at.

898
00:54:09,720 --> 00:54:14,240
So that's why we have
a class of models

899
00:54:14,240 --> 00:54:18,840
that aim at capturing the
sequential nature of how

900
00:54:18,840 --> 00:54:20,160
text appears.

901
00:54:20,160 --> 00:54:23,530
So we're going to talk
about RNNs, which stands

902
00:54:23,530 --> 00:54:26,850
for Recurrent Neural Network.

903
00:54:26,850 --> 00:54:32,050
So what RNNs do is,
instead of processing words

904
00:54:32,050 --> 00:54:35,810
one at a time, what
they do is they

905
00:54:35,810 --> 00:54:42,090
keep a hidden representation
of the sentence so far,

906
00:54:42,090 --> 00:54:46,890
and they consider
tokens one at a time.

907
00:54:46,890 --> 00:54:50,130
So as I mentioned before,
this technique was actually

908
00:54:50,130 --> 00:54:55,650
introduced a fair amount of
time ago, so in the '80s.

909
00:54:55,650 --> 00:55:01,010
And what this model does is
it takes into consideration

910
00:55:01,010 --> 00:55:05,290
the order at which words
appeared or tokens appeared.

911
00:55:05,290 --> 00:55:10,350
And so in this
example, you start the,

912
00:55:10,350 --> 00:55:13,350
I guess, processing at the
very beginning of the sentence.

913
00:55:13,350 --> 00:55:18,250
You have some dummy hidden
states that is called A,

914
00:55:18,250 --> 00:55:21,010
typically denoted
A or H. It's called

915
00:55:21,010 --> 00:55:26,510
the hidden state, activation, or
even sometimes a context vector.

916
00:55:26,510 --> 00:55:29,710
And you have some
kind of a module that

917
00:55:29,710 --> 00:55:34,790
takes into account the
hidden state so far

918
00:55:34,790 --> 00:55:41,590
and the word at time step
t, so here time step 1.

919
00:55:41,590 --> 00:55:47,070
So here what it does is it takes
in the meaning of the sentence

920
00:55:47,070 --> 00:55:49,270
so far and takes
into consideration

921
00:55:49,270 --> 00:55:52,230
the word that is happening now.

922
00:55:52,230 --> 00:55:56,510
And it produces an
output vector that

923
00:55:56,510 --> 00:55:59,770
here can be used to try
to predict the next word.

924
00:55:59,770 --> 00:56:02,670
So for instance here we
have this hidden state

925
00:56:02,670 --> 00:56:06,630
and the representation
of the word

926
00:56:06,630 --> 00:56:09,630
that then you have some
matrix multiplications

927
00:56:09,630 --> 00:56:12,070
in this blue box.

928
00:56:12,070 --> 00:56:14,390
And you have an
output vector that you

929
00:56:14,390 --> 00:56:20,560
try to train on
predicting the next words.

930
00:56:20,560 --> 00:56:30,760
And then you keep on
doing that by keeping

931
00:56:30,760 --> 00:56:33,760
track of these hidden states.

932
00:56:33,760 --> 00:56:35,840
And so you repeat the process.

933
00:56:35,840 --> 00:56:39,800
And I guess the way you would
interpret these hidden states

934
00:56:39,800 --> 00:56:46,740
is it's a representation of
the sequence process so far.

935
00:56:49,720 --> 00:56:56,840
So the good thing with RNNs
is now the word order matters.

936
00:56:56,840 --> 00:57:00,920
And you're also able
to encode the sentence

937
00:57:00,920 --> 00:57:02,380
in a more natural way.

938
00:57:04,920 --> 00:57:07,520
So let's see roughly
how it works.

939
00:57:07,520 --> 00:57:10,580
So we have the same
favorite example,

940
00:57:10,580 --> 00:57:12,480
so cute teddy bear is reading.

941
00:57:12,480 --> 00:57:17,970
So you would have the token
A. You want one-hot encoding

942
00:57:17,970 --> 00:57:18,970
vector.

943
00:57:18,970 --> 00:57:20,690
You pass it through
your network.

944
00:57:20,690 --> 00:57:22,490
You compute the hidden state.

945
00:57:22,490 --> 00:57:25,490
You try to predict cute.

946
00:57:25,490 --> 00:57:30,810
But then you keep track
of the hidden state.

947
00:57:30,810 --> 00:57:34,370
And then you input that
into another module.

948
00:57:34,370 --> 00:57:37,290
And then you also
consider the next words.

949
00:57:37,290 --> 00:57:40,530
So you consider not only the
word itself, but also the hidden

950
00:57:40,530 --> 00:57:43,110
state of this sentence so far.

951
00:57:43,110 --> 00:57:47,470
And you try to predict the next
word again, and again and again.

952
00:57:51,130 --> 00:57:52,160
So this is RNN.

953
00:57:54,730 --> 00:57:59,610
So RNNs were used
for a bunch of tasks,

954
00:57:59,610 --> 00:58:02,370
and just like mapping that
back to the categories

955
00:58:02,370 --> 00:58:04,690
that we saw before.

956
00:58:04,690 --> 00:58:08,330
For classification
purposes, you can basically

957
00:58:08,330 --> 00:58:14,110
use the hidden state of the
last word in your sentence.

958
00:58:14,110 --> 00:58:17,510
For instance, if
you want to predict

959
00:58:17,510 --> 00:58:19,750
like the sentiment
of a review, you

960
00:58:19,750 --> 00:58:23,150
would take basically
the last vector here

961
00:58:23,150 --> 00:58:25,310
and try to project
it into the space

962
00:58:25,310 --> 00:58:28,450
of the predictions or the labels
that you want to predict on.

963
00:58:28,450 --> 00:58:30,830
So for instance, if you
want positive or negative,

964
00:58:30,830 --> 00:58:33,430
you basically project that
vector onto that space.

965
00:58:33,430 --> 00:58:34,790
You can do that here.

966
00:58:34,790 --> 00:58:37,710
For multi-classification,
so you would basically

967
00:58:37,710 --> 00:58:41,190
have the representation
of the token of interest,

968
00:58:41,190 --> 00:58:43,750
and you would project that.

969
00:58:43,750 --> 00:58:47,430
Or for generation,
you would basically

970
00:58:47,430 --> 00:58:52,030
process the whole
source text, and then

971
00:58:52,030 --> 00:58:56,390
have a context vector, a.k.a.

972
00:58:56,390 --> 00:58:58,110
activation vector, a.k.a.

973
00:58:58,110 --> 00:59:02,430
hidden state at the
end of your processing,

974
00:59:02,430 --> 00:59:09,230
which will then be used to
decode the output prediction.

975
00:59:09,230 --> 00:59:14,800
So this is how you would use
an RNN for each of these tasks.

976
00:59:14,800 --> 00:59:21,720
So the reason why you have not
really heard of RNNs these days

977
00:59:21,720 --> 00:59:26,760
is because they had some
pros, but a lot of cons.

978
00:59:26,760 --> 00:59:31,560
So one of the cons is that
the meaning of the sentence

979
00:59:31,560 --> 00:59:35,450
is basically solely encapsulated
into this hidden state.

980
00:59:39,240 --> 00:59:43,000
So you have this problem
of long-range dependencies,

981
00:59:43,000 --> 00:59:49,080
which basically impacts your
ability to quote, unquote,

982
00:59:49,080 --> 00:59:54,400
"remember" what the
model saw in the past,

983
00:59:54,400 --> 00:59:57,560
which is why you have another
class of models that try

984
00:59:57,560 --> 00:59:59,600
to build on RNNs.

985
00:59:59,600 --> 01:00:05,960
So this one is called LSTMs,
Long Short-Term Memory.

986
01:00:05,960 --> 01:00:12,200
And the goal of that extension
is to have the way to somehow

987
01:00:12,200 --> 01:00:16,180
keep track of the things that
are quote, unquote, "important"

988
01:00:16,180 --> 01:00:20,060
to remember, on top of the
hidden state that we talked

989
01:00:20,060 --> 01:00:20,560
about.

990
01:00:20,560 --> 01:00:26,580
So here you have a of t,
which is your activation,

991
01:00:26,580 --> 01:00:29,480
basically the sequence
so far encoded in there.

992
01:00:29,480 --> 01:00:33,220
And then you have
another quantity

993
01:00:33,220 --> 01:00:36,020
that you track that is
called the cell state.

994
01:00:36,020 --> 01:00:39,220
It's denoted c here.

995
01:00:39,220 --> 01:00:45,200
So this architecture aims
at improving that piece,

996
01:00:45,200 --> 01:00:49,340
but I guess it was
not perfect either.

997
01:00:49,340 --> 01:00:55,260
But yeah, so that
was the main issue

998
01:00:55,260 --> 01:00:58,860
of RNN-based methods,
which is that they

999
01:00:58,860 --> 01:01:01,800
have this issue of forgetting
what was in the past.

1000
01:01:01,800 --> 01:01:03,500
So you will see
in the literature

1001
01:01:03,500 --> 01:01:08,420
that this phenomenon is
called vanishing gradient.

1002
01:01:08,420 --> 01:01:11,590
And the reason why it's called
that way-- so I know we're

1003
01:01:11,590 --> 01:01:15,790
running out of time, but I'm
going to just explain that part.

1004
01:01:15,790 --> 01:01:22,270
So in order for you to predict,
let's say, the last words,

1005
01:01:22,270 --> 01:01:25,950
you're basically dependent
on every hidden state

1006
01:01:25,950 --> 01:01:27,370
that came before that.

1007
01:01:30,590 --> 01:01:32,550
So far so good?

1008
01:01:32,550 --> 01:01:38,390
And so whenever you want to
update the weights of your model

1009
01:01:38,390 --> 01:01:43,670
to match the prediction here
with the actual prediction, when

1010
01:01:43,670 --> 01:01:46,830
you do the back
propagation, you somehow

1011
01:01:46,830 --> 01:01:53,830
need to take into account that
the value here is basically

1012
01:01:53,830 --> 01:01:56,930
not only a matter
of this computation,

1013
01:01:56,930 --> 01:01:59,122
but also this computation
or this computation

1014
01:01:59,122 --> 01:02:01,080
that basically happened
in a sequential manner.

1015
01:02:03,750 --> 01:02:11,210
So you have this phenomenon
of trying to, I guess,

1016
01:02:11,210 --> 01:02:13,770
back-propagate through time.

1017
01:02:13,770 --> 01:02:17,090
But the problem is,
in practice when

1018
01:02:17,090 --> 01:02:19,430
you write that down-- so
it's a very ugly formula.

1019
01:02:19,430 --> 01:02:21,810
But when you write
that down, it ends up

1020
01:02:21,810 --> 01:02:28,330
being a product of a
bunch of quantities

1021
01:02:28,330 --> 01:02:32,210
that can-- so if it's greater
than 1, then it's exploding.

1022
01:02:32,210 --> 01:02:34,528
If it's less than
1, it's vanishing.

1023
01:02:34,528 --> 01:02:37,070
Because if you multiply a lot
of things that are less than 1,

1024
01:02:37,070 --> 01:02:38,697
it just goes to 0.

1025
01:02:38,697 --> 01:02:40,530
So I guess if you have
something that you're

1026
01:02:40,530 --> 01:02:44,210
trying to update that
goes to 0, basically

1027
01:02:44,210 --> 01:02:46,970
you have trouble just
doing your updates.

1028
01:02:46,970 --> 01:02:49,330
So that's a
high-level intuition.

1029
01:02:49,330 --> 01:02:50,870
This is not the
focus of this class,

1030
01:02:50,870 --> 01:02:53,010
which is why I'm not
going into the detail

1031
01:02:53,010 --> 01:02:54,190
of this ugly formulas.

1032
01:02:54,190 --> 01:02:59,450
But I hope you get the idea
that for remembering things

1033
01:02:59,450 --> 01:03:01,930
from the past, it's
not doing a great job,

1034
01:03:01,930 --> 01:03:08,160
because of this sequential,
I guess, characteristic.

1035
01:03:10,860 --> 01:03:13,500
Does that make sense?

1036
01:03:13,500 --> 01:03:16,800
OK, I hope the next thing
will make a bit more sense.

1037
01:03:16,800 --> 01:03:19,700
But before that, I'll
just recap what we saw.

1038
01:03:19,700 --> 01:03:24,540
So our goal is to
represent text.

1039
01:03:24,540 --> 01:03:27,820
So we first started
with representing

1040
01:03:27,820 --> 01:03:33,180
words or tokens, which was what
we tried to do with Word2vec.

1041
01:03:33,180 --> 01:03:37,700
And we saw that it was a good
way to leverage proxy tasks

1042
01:03:37,700 --> 01:03:39,780
to learn this representation.

1043
01:03:39,780 --> 01:03:42,763
But we had a bunch
of limitations.

1044
01:03:42,763 --> 01:03:44,180
And one of them
that you mentioned

1045
01:03:44,180 --> 01:03:48,180
was that this was not
aware of the context.

1046
01:03:48,180 --> 01:03:51,740
And also the word
order didn't count.

1047
01:03:51,740 --> 01:03:54,700
And so you have this
other class of methods

1048
01:03:54,700 --> 01:04:00,980
that is able to take into
consideration the words,

1049
01:04:00,980 --> 01:04:04,620
but then they have some
trouble keeping track of things

1050
01:04:04,620 --> 01:04:07,040
when the sequence
gets very long.

1051
01:04:07,040 --> 01:04:10,160
And you have this problem
of vanishing gradients

1052
01:04:10,160 --> 01:04:12,780
or long-range dependencies.

1053
01:04:12,780 --> 01:04:14,240
So whenever you
see this term, it's

1054
01:04:14,240 --> 01:04:16,880
basically referring to that.

1055
01:04:16,880 --> 01:04:18,980
And also another thing
that I have not mentioned,

1056
01:04:18,980 --> 01:04:22,360
but the computations
are very slow.

1057
01:04:22,360 --> 01:04:26,720
So when you want to train
these models, at training time,

1058
01:04:26,720 --> 01:04:29,640
in order to predict
this word, you basically

1059
01:04:29,640 --> 01:04:34,960
need to compute all these
hidden states before.

1060
01:04:34,960 --> 01:04:39,920
So when your sequence
gets very long,

1061
01:04:39,920 --> 01:04:42,220
it just takes a very long time.

1062
01:04:46,680 --> 01:04:51,660
So for all of these reasons,
for I guess what reason.

1063
01:04:51,660 --> 01:05:00,160
So for the fact that the model
has trouble remembering things

1064
01:05:00,160 --> 01:05:06,890
from the past, people have tried
having more direct connections

1065
01:05:06,890 --> 01:05:09,970
between something and
the thing from the past,

1066
01:05:09,970 --> 01:05:14,130
and this is the idea
behind attention.

1067
01:05:14,130 --> 01:05:18,570
So what attention
does is it tries

1068
01:05:18,570 --> 01:05:23,690
to have a direct link between
what we're trying to predict

1069
01:05:23,690 --> 01:05:26,290
and something from the past.

1070
01:05:26,290 --> 01:05:28,570
So in this example,
let's suppose

1071
01:05:28,570 --> 01:05:32,530
I'm trying to translate
an English sentence

1072
01:05:32,530 --> 01:05:34,850
into a French one.

1073
01:05:34,850 --> 01:05:38,070
So here I guess the
input sentence is given.

1074
01:05:38,070 --> 01:05:40,330
I'm computing the hidden state.

1075
01:05:40,330 --> 01:05:41,910
I'm processing
words one at a time.

1076
01:05:41,910 --> 01:05:43,770
This is my traditional RNN.

1077
01:05:43,770 --> 01:05:45,670
So "a cute teddy
bear is reading."

1078
01:05:45,670 --> 01:05:50,330
So here I have a hidden
state that I'm then decoding.

1079
01:05:50,330 --> 01:05:54,170
And you can imagine
that when wanting

1080
01:05:54,170 --> 01:05:59,250
to generate the next
word of my translation,

1081
01:05:59,250 --> 01:06:07,860
it would be great if I knew
what word I'm trying to predict.

1082
01:06:07,860 --> 01:06:09,380
Or in other words,
it would be great

1083
01:06:09,380 --> 01:06:16,660
if I could take a peek at a
certain area of the input text.

1084
01:06:16,660 --> 01:06:18,940
So the idea behind
attention is to have

1085
01:06:18,940 --> 01:06:23,460
a direct link between what
you're trying to predict

1086
01:06:23,460 --> 01:06:26,900
and things before.

1087
01:06:26,900 --> 01:06:29,620
This is the idea
behind attention.

1088
01:06:29,620 --> 01:06:32,220
And so it was
introduced in 2014.

1089
01:06:32,220 --> 01:06:36,060
And yeah, again, this
is trying to solve

1090
01:06:36,060 --> 01:06:39,750
for these long-range
dependency issues.

1091
01:06:42,900 --> 01:06:45,380
And so yeah, this example
we want to do that.

1092
01:06:45,380 --> 01:06:51,820
And this concept is going to
actually be key for this class.

1093
01:06:51,820 --> 01:06:56,140
Because we're going to see
that the attention mechanism is

1094
01:06:56,140 --> 01:06:58,060
the thing that is going
to make everything--

1095
01:06:58,060 --> 01:07:02,080
I mean, most of the things work.

1096
01:07:02,080 --> 01:07:05,280
And this is actually
the main principle

1097
01:07:05,280 --> 01:07:08,680
that the transformer
paper relies on.

1098
01:07:08,680 --> 01:07:12,080
So the transformer, which
is the core architecture

1099
01:07:12,080 --> 01:07:15,800
that we will see in this
class, has been introduced

1100
01:07:15,800 --> 01:07:19,840
or was introduced in
2017 in this paper named

1101
01:07:19,840 --> 01:07:22,440
Attention is All You Need.

1102
01:07:22,440 --> 01:07:26,240
So even from the title, you
can see that the authors wanted

1103
01:07:26,240 --> 01:07:28,640
to just rely on that part.

1104
01:07:28,640 --> 01:07:31,960
So what the authors
tried to do was

1105
01:07:31,960 --> 01:07:37,600
to move away from this
sequential way of processing

1106
01:07:37,600 --> 01:07:42,000
the text, and instead
let the model just

1107
01:07:42,000 --> 01:07:49,000
have direct connections with
all parts of the text at once.

1108
01:07:49,000 --> 01:07:52,320
So that is called
self-attention.

1109
01:07:52,320 --> 01:07:55,160
So they tried that
on translation tasks.

1110
01:07:55,160 --> 01:08:00,730
And they just realized that
it was giving great results.

1111
01:08:00,730 --> 01:08:03,730
So back to the example
that we're still using,

1112
01:08:03,730 --> 01:08:07,890
a cute teddy bear is reading
Here what we would say

1113
01:08:07,890 --> 01:08:12,610
is that in order to
compute the representation

1114
01:08:12,610 --> 01:08:16,250
of the token teddy
bear, we're going

1115
01:08:16,250 --> 01:08:24,410
to look at all the other
tokens in the sequence at once,

1116
01:08:24,410 --> 01:08:27,410
and directly with direct links.

1117
01:08:27,410 --> 01:08:29,750
So I guess back to
your question-- here,

1118
01:08:29,750 --> 01:08:32,330
we would have a
representation of teddy bear

1119
01:08:32,330 --> 01:08:36,729
that would be unique to the
context that it is part of.

1120
01:08:36,729 --> 01:08:41,250
So back to your question about
riverbank and robbing a bank,

1121
01:08:41,250 --> 01:08:46,170
like here the bank would have
different representations.

1122
01:08:46,170 --> 01:08:49,290
So this is the idea.

1123
01:08:49,290 --> 01:08:51,400
I guess, does the idea
roughly make sense?

1124
01:08:55,850 --> 01:08:59,808
And again, this is called
the self-attention mechanism.

1125
01:08:59,808 --> 01:09:02,160
Afshine, how am I doing on time?

1126
01:09:02,160 --> 01:09:03,010
8.

1127
01:09:03,010 --> 01:09:04,210
I have 8?

1128
01:09:04,210 --> 01:09:06,710
OK, cool.

1129
01:09:06,710 --> 01:09:09,550
OK, so this is the idea.

1130
01:09:09,550 --> 01:09:11,069
So now I'm going
to just introduce

1131
01:09:11,069 --> 01:09:15,189
another set of ideas
which is more terminology

1132
01:09:15,189 --> 01:09:17,910
but is going to
be very important.

1133
01:09:17,910 --> 01:09:22,510
So when you want to express
something in terms of something

1134
01:09:22,510 --> 01:09:30,870
else, we use the words "query,"
"key," and "value," Q, K and V.

1135
01:09:30,870 --> 01:09:37,189
So in this example, our
goal is to figure out

1136
01:09:37,189 --> 01:09:43,710
what other tokens is the query
teddy bear more similar to.

1137
01:09:43,710 --> 01:09:46,710
So here the question
is, OK, you have a query

1138
01:09:46,710 --> 01:09:52,670
and you want to see what
other tokens are most similar.

1139
01:09:52,670 --> 01:09:55,400
And so what you're
going to do is

1140
01:09:55,400 --> 01:09:59,040
to look at all the other
tokens which are basically

1141
01:09:59,040 --> 01:10:03,120
composed of keys and values.

1142
01:10:03,120 --> 01:10:06,800
So we're going to compare
the query to the key

1143
01:10:06,800 --> 01:10:13,040
to quantify how similar your
query is to a given key,

1144
01:10:13,040 --> 01:10:16,720
and take the
corresponding value.

1145
01:10:16,720 --> 01:10:18,260
So we'll see that
in this example,

1146
01:10:18,260 --> 01:10:20,760
so let's suppose you want to
express teddy bear in terms

1147
01:10:20,760 --> 01:10:21,920
of everything else.

1148
01:10:21,920 --> 01:10:23,295
What you're going
to do is you're

1149
01:10:23,295 --> 01:10:25,800
going to take the
query teddy bear,

1150
01:10:25,800 --> 01:10:31,320
and you're going to compare that
query with all the other keys

1151
01:10:31,320 --> 01:10:35,240
to see which element
is most similar,

1152
01:10:35,240 --> 01:10:38,160
and then weight the
more similar ones

1153
01:10:38,160 --> 01:10:41,640
and take their associated value.

1154
01:10:41,640 --> 01:10:48,060
So that's a very high level
idea of how these things are.

1155
01:10:48,060 --> 01:10:50,783
Of course, we're going to
see exactly how they work.

1156
01:10:50,783 --> 01:10:51,950
But that's the general idea.

1157
01:10:55,100 --> 01:10:56,340
OK, cool.

1158
01:10:56,340 --> 01:10:58,960
And speaking of query
and key and value,

1159
01:10:58,960 --> 01:11:03,660
we will also see that one
benefit of expressing things

1160
01:11:03,660 --> 01:11:09,820
this way is that we
can express doing

1161
01:11:09,820 --> 01:11:12,900
this self-attention computation
across the whole sequence

1162
01:11:12,900 --> 01:11:16,340
in a matrix format.

1163
01:11:16,340 --> 01:11:20,000
And GPUs love matrices.

1164
01:11:20,000 --> 01:11:24,180
So it's really made for
the hardware that we have.

1165
01:11:24,180 --> 01:11:26,660
And I guess what
I mentioned here

1166
01:11:26,660 --> 01:11:30,220
can be expressed in
a form of softmax

1167
01:11:30,220 --> 01:11:33,620
of the query and the key,
which is basically a way

1168
01:11:33,620 --> 01:11:39,580
to get some kinds of
weights of which values

1169
01:11:39,580 --> 01:11:40,640
will be more important.

1170
01:11:40,640 --> 01:11:42,557
So for instance, if a
value is more important,

1171
01:11:42,557 --> 01:11:43,700
you have bigger weight.

1172
01:11:43,700 --> 01:11:45,325
And another one will
be less important,

1173
01:11:45,325 --> 01:11:46,700
you'll have a smaller weight.

1174
01:11:46,700 --> 01:11:51,340
And you basically multiply
that by the value.

1175
01:11:51,340 --> 01:11:55,090
So don't worry, we'll have
a detailed example after.

1176
01:11:55,090 --> 01:12:00,130
So if it still feels very
high-level fuzzy, don't worry.

1177
01:12:00,130 --> 01:12:05,830
We'll have a
detailed walkthrough.

1178
01:12:05,830 --> 01:12:08,570
And yes, so this
is how it works.

1179
01:12:08,570 --> 01:12:11,670
OK, cool.

1180
01:12:11,670 --> 01:12:16,730
Any questions on what
self-attention is?

1181
01:12:16,730 --> 01:12:17,230
Yeah.

1182
01:12:40,990 --> 01:12:41,930
Great, great question.

1183
01:12:41,930 --> 01:12:44,287
So the question is, what
is value, what is key?

1184
01:12:44,287 --> 01:12:45,370
I guess, how to get those?

1185
01:12:45,370 --> 01:12:47,150
What do they mean?

1186
01:12:47,150 --> 01:12:49,790
So first of all, I just want
to say that these quantities,

1187
01:12:49,790 --> 01:12:51,290
they are learned.

1188
01:12:51,290 --> 01:12:53,450
So you are not fixing them.

1189
01:12:53,450 --> 01:12:55,990
But from an
interpretation standpoint,

1190
01:12:55,990 --> 01:12:58,730
you can interpret
that the key is there

1191
01:12:58,730 --> 01:13:04,570
for you to figure out which one
is most similar to the query.

1192
01:13:04,570 --> 01:13:08,010
And the value is
the actual value

1193
01:13:08,010 --> 01:13:10,870
that is associated
with that element.

1194
01:13:10,870 --> 01:13:14,530
So here, you will have
something like you

1195
01:13:14,530 --> 01:13:18,410
want to express this in
terms of all the values.

1196
01:13:18,410 --> 01:13:20,330
So the weights in
your weighted average

1197
01:13:20,330 --> 01:13:23,210
will be basically the
dot product between--

1198
01:13:23,210 --> 01:13:26,290
basically-- between
the query and the key.

1199
01:13:26,290 --> 01:13:31,570
And the value will be the
actual vector that you will use.

1200
01:13:31,570 --> 01:13:33,210
But again, these
things are learned.

1201
01:13:33,210 --> 01:13:34,710
And something I
have not mentioned,

1202
01:13:34,710 --> 01:13:36,970
but you mentioned it
correctly, so we're

1203
01:13:36,970 --> 01:13:40,830
going to actually do projections
to obtain these quantities.

1204
01:13:40,830 --> 01:13:43,340
And these projections are
actually learned by the model.

1205
01:13:48,050 --> 01:13:50,180
That's good?

1206
01:13:50,180 --> 01:13:52,180
OK, cool.

1207
01:13:52,180 --> 01:13:57,920
So with that, we have
15 minutes, right,

1208
01:13:57,920 --> 01:14:01,792
to talk about the architecture.

1209
01:14:01,792 --> 01:14:08,500
OK, so at a very
high level, in order

1210
01:14:08,500 --> 01:14:12,300
to make the self-attention
mechanism happen,

1211
01:14:12,300 --> 01:14:15,100
the authors propose
an architecture

1212
01:14:15,100 --> 01:14:19,660
that is composed of two
parts, an encoder, which

1213
01:14:19,660 --> 01:14:22,860
is on the left
side, and a decoder,

1214
01:14:22,860 --> 01:14:26,340
which is on the right side.

1215
01:14:26,340 --> 01:14:29,740
So the application that
they have is translation.

1216
01:14:29,740 --> 01:14:31,900
So what will go
through the encoder

1217
01:14:31,900 --> 01:14:37,380
is the input text in
your source language.

1218
01:14:37,380 --> 01:14:39,300
And what is going to
go through the decoder

1219
01:14:39,300 --> 01:14:43,860
is the target language
that you're predicting.

1220
01:14:43,860 --> 01:14:47,990
So the high-level
idea is you're going

1221
01:14:47,990 --> 01:14:53,630
to compute meaningful
embeddings from your input text

1222
01:14:53,630 --> 01:14:57,310
by passing them
through the encoder.

1223
01:14:57,310 --> 01:15:01,390
And you want that self-attention
mechanism to apply,

1224
01:15:01,390 --> 01:15:05,310
meaning you want to compute
representations of each token

1225
01:15:05,310 --> 01:15:07,870
as a function of others.

1226
01:15:07,870 --> 01:15:13,590
And you do that by using a layer
called the attention layer.

1227
01:15:13,590 --> 01:15:15,510
So multi-head attention
layer, but multi-head

1228
01:15:15,510 --> 01:15:19,870
is just doing this
computation in different ways

1229
01:15:19,870 --> 01:15:23,150
to just allow the model to
learn different representations

1230
01:15:23,150 --> 01:15:25,990
or different projections.

1231
01:15:25,990 --> 01:15:33,910
But the idea here is you are
going to input your input text,

1232
01:15:33,910 --> 01:15:36,990
and all the tokens
in your input text

1233
01:15:36,990 --> 01:15:40,270
are going to attend
to one another.

1234
01:15:40,270 --> 01:15:42,650
So for instance, a cute
teddy bear is reading,

1235
01:15:42,650 --> 01:15:46,050
you are going to compute
the representation

1236
01:15:46,050 --> 01:15:50,010
of all the tokens in
this text basically

1237
01:15:50,010 --> 01:15:52,330
as a function of others.

1238
01:15:52,330 --> 01:15:55,050
And you're going to do that
with the encoder, so here

1239
01:15:55,050 --> 01:15:57,530
with the multi-head attention.

1240
01:15:57,530 --> 01:16:00,630
And then you have a
feedforward layer,

1241
01:16:00,630 --> 01:16:03,850
which is just to
let the model learn

1242
01:16:03,850 --> 01:16:05,770
another kind of projection.

1243
01:16:05,770 --> 01:16:08,970
And what you're going
to obtain at the end

1244
01:16:08,970 --> 01:16:14,290
of your encoding process
is rich representations

1245
01:16:14,290 --> 01:16:17,120
of the tokens from
the input sentence.

1246
01:16:19,690 --> 01:16:21,090
So far, so good?

1247
01:16:21,090 --> 01:16:26,430
But now your goal is to actually
translate the input sentence.

1248
01:16:26,430 --> 01:16:32,570
So what you're going to do
is to start your translation

1249
01:16:32,570 --> 01:16:35,870
with, let's suppose, the
beginning of sentence token,

1250
01:16:35,870 --> 01:16:37,850
so your first token.

1251
01:16:37,850 --> 01:16:43,300
And what you're going to do
is use all the representations

1252
01:16:43,300 --> 01:16:46,020
from your input
sentence in order

1253
01:16:46,020 --> 01:16:50,260
to figure out what
to predict next.

1254
01:16:50,260 --> 01:16:56,680
So this what I just said is
the cross-attention layer,

1255
01:16:56,680 --> 01:17:01,700
which is the one that is
the second, so this one,

1256
01:17:01,700 --> 01:17:03,942
which basically--

1257
01:17:03,942 --> 01:17:05,400
I'm not sure if
you see the arrows,

1258
01:17:05,400 --> 01:17:07,900
but there are two arrows
coming from the encoder, one

1259
01:17:07,900 --> 01:17:10,460
arrow coming from the decoder.

1260
01:17:10,460 --> 01:17:14,050
Can anyone tell me what
the arrow from the decoder

1261
01:17:14,050 --> 01:17:14,550
represents?

1262
01:17:14,550 --> 01:17:15,970
Is decoder a query key or value?

1263
01:17:22,376 --> 01:17:27,900
I guess there is 1
over 3, 33% chance.

1264
01:17:27,900 --> 01:17:30,260
Who wants to try?

1265
01:17:30,260 --> 01:17:31,230
Is it key?

1266
01:17:31,230 --> 01:17:31,730
OK.

1267
01:17:35,260 --> 01:17:36,140
Query?

1268
01:17:36,140 --> 01:17:36,980
OK.

1269
01:17:36,980 --> 01:17:40,340
So the way to think
about it is you're

1270
01:17:40,340 --> 01:17:46,200
trying to ask yourself, what are
the words from the input that

1271
01:17:46,200 --> 01:17:48,080
matter.

1272
01:17:48,080 --> 01:17:49,490
Right?

1273
01:17:49,490 --> 01:17:51,880
So basically, you
want know, given

1274
01:17:51,880 --> 01:17:57,480
your query, what are the
elements from the inputs that

1275
01:17:57,480 --> 01:17:58,140
matter?

1276
01:17:58,140 --> 01:18:00,760
So here, this arrow
is indeed the query,

1277
01:18:00,760 --> 01:18:05,120
because this is the thing
that you want to figure out.

1278
01:18:05,120 --> 01:18:06,880
And the keys and
values are actually

1279
01:18:06,880 --> 01:18:09,480
coming from the encoder,
which are basically

1280
01:18:09,480 --> 01:18:14,320
coming from the input sequence.

1281
01:18:14,320 --> 01:18:16,860
And then you have
another attention layer,

1282
01:18:16,860 --> 01:18:17,660
which is this one.

1283
01:18:17,660 --> 01:18:23,680
And that one is
trying to figure out

1284
01:18:23,680 --> 01:18:29,000
what other tokens of the output
sentence that you're decoding

1285
01:18:29,000 --> 01:18:32,560
is going to be useful to
predict the next token.

1286
01:18:32,560 --> 01:18:35,280
So let's suppose
you start decoding

1287
01:18:35,280 --> 01:18:40,250
and you say, un ours en
peluche, which is in French.

1288
01:18:40,250 --> 01:18:44,290
To predict the next word, you
want to basically figure out

1289
01:18:44,290 --> 01:18:47,770
what are the tokens
translated so far that

1290
01:18:47,770 --> 01:18:51,270
are going to be useful
to predict the next word.

1291
01:18:51,270 --> 01:18:54,510
So this is what this
attention layer is about.

1292
01:18:54,510 --> 01:18:58,010
And it's called
masked, because it only

1293
01:18:58,010 --> 01:19:03,290
looks at the tokens
that translated so far.

1294
01:19:03,290 --> 01:19:06,018
It does not look at
tokens that were not

1295
01:19:06,018 --> 01:19:08,310
translated, because of course
they were not translated.

1296
01:19:08,310 --> 01:19:11,650
So there's no way, like on
the right side of the token

1297
01:19:11,650 --> 01:19:12,900
that you're trying to predict.

1298
01:19:15,770 --> 01:19:17,710
Cool.

1299
01:19:17,710 --> 01:19:21,350
So at a very high level, you
have this attention layer,

1300
01:19:21,350 --> 01:19:24,970
which is present in the encoder,
which is present in the decoder,

1301
01:19:24,970 --> 01:19:28,830
but it has several,
I guess, use cases.

1302
01:19:28,830 --> 01:19:36,450
So the attention layer here
aims at computing embeddings

1303
01:19:36,450 --> 01:19:42,310
from the input sentence as
a function of themselves.

1304
01:19:42,310 --> 01:19:44,530
And then the ones
from the decoder,

1305
01:19:44,530 --> 01:19:47,310
so the first one, the
masked self-attention layer,

1306
01:19:47,310 --> 01:19:53,070
aims at expressing something as
a function of everything that

1307
01:19:53,070 --> 01:19:56,430
has been decoded so far.

1308
01:19:56,430 --> 01:19:58,670
And the second one, the
cross-attention layer,

1309
01:19:58,670 --> 01:20:02,150
tries to express things
as a function of what

1310
01:20:02,150 --> 01:20:05,430
has been seen in the input.

1311
01:20:05,430 --> 01:20:10,510
So here, given
that you are having

1312
01:20:10,510 --> 01:20:13,990
direct links to
different tokens,

1313
01:20:13,990 --> 01:20:17,870
you don't have this
sense of order.

1314
01:20:17,870 --> 01:20:20,790
Because in the RNN,
you are basically

1315
01:20:20,790 --> 01:20:23,310
expressing things one at a time.

1316
01:20:23,310 --> 01:20:26,490
So you had some sense
of the word order,

1317
01:20:26,490 --> 01:20:28,230
but here you don't
have it, because it's

1318
01:20:28,230 --> 01:20:33,070
like a direct link, which
is why you have position

1319
01:20:33,070 --> 01:20:37,600
encodings, which
are there to inform

1320
01:20:37,600 --> 01:20:40,920
on the position of the
word in the sequence.

1321
01:20:40,920 --> 01:20:43,520
So we're not going to
dig into that today,

1322
01:20:43,520 --> 01:20:46,960
but I just want
to call that out.

1323
01:20:46,960 --> 01:20:48,520
So at a very high
level, and we're

1324
01:20:48,520 --> 01:20:51,480
going to see this in the
detailed example, what

1325
01:20:51,480 --> 01:20:56,320
we do is in order to translate
a sentence from source language

1326
01:20:56,320 --> 01:20:58,960
to target language,
we're first going

1327
01:20:58,960 --> 01:21:03,960
to tokenize the text, so
dividing into arbitrary units.

1328
01:21:03,960 --> 01:21:07,200
We're going to learn an
embedding for these tokens.

1329
01:21:07,200 --> 01:21:09,760
So this is what the
input embedding is about.

1330
01:21:09,760 --> 01:21:12,840
Then we're going to add
some encoding with respect

1331
01:21:12,840 --> 01:21:14,240
to the position.

1332
01:21:14,240 --> 01:21:19,000
We're not going to talk about
it today, but just good to note.

1333
01:21:19,000 --> 01:21:22,360
And then we go
through the encoder.

1334
01:21:22,360 --> 01:21:26,320
So the encoder
tries to figure out

1335
01:21:26,320 --> 01:21:29,320
how to express things as
a function of other things

1336
01:21:29,320 --> 01:21:30,680
from the inputs.

1337
01:21:30,680 --> 01:21:35,500
So it does that in the
multi-head attention layer.

1338
01:21:35,500 --> 01:21:37,800
And then it goes through a
feedforward neural network,

1339
01:21:37,800 --> 01:21:43,220
which is just a way to just
project the vectors to just

1340
01:21:43,220 --> 01:21:48,300
have some more degrees of
freedom to learn things.

1341
01:21:48,300 --> 01:21:51,700
And then once you have these
representations from the input,

1342
01:21:51,700 --> 01:21:56,060
you're then going to
start your translation.

1343
01:21:56,060 --> 01:21:58,540
So you start with the BOS token.

1344
01:21:58,540 --> 01:22:00,980
And what you're
trying to do is figure

1345
01:22:00,980 --> 01:22:03,260
out what the next word is.

1346
01:22:03,260 --> 01:22:05,740
So you're going to
see, OK, what are

1347
01:22:05,740 --> 01:22:08,180
the words that were
translated so far that

1348
01:22:08,180 --> 01:22:09,920
are useful for translation.

1349
01:22:09,920 --> 01:22:14,900
So this is what the masked
multi-head attention layer does.

1350
01:22:14,900 --> 01:22:16,800
And then you have
another attention layer,

1351
01:22:16,800 --> 01:22:22,820
which is about expressing
things as a function of what

1352
01:22:22,820 --> 01:22:26,820
was in the input, which is
the cross-attention layer

1353
01:22:26,820 --> 01:22:27,440
over there.

1354
01:22:27,440 --> 01:22:30,580
And then you have a feedforward
neural network to, again,

1355
01:22:30,580 --> 01:22:32,790
give some more
degrees of freedom.

1356
01:22:32,790 --> 01:22:38,590
And at the end of the day, you
have a vector that you then

1357
01:22:38,590 --> 01:22:40,702
go through softmax.

1358
01:22:40,702 --> 01:22:46,470
And it just is a way for you
to guess what is the next word.

1359
01:22:46,470 --> 01:22:51,070
So you have a vector
of vocabulary size.

1360
01:22:51,070 --> 01:22:54,870
And you're going to use
these values to determine

1361
01:22:54,870 --> 01:22:56,090
what is your next word.

1362
01:22:58,990 --> 01:23:01,550
Easy, right?

1363
01:23:01,550 --> 01:23:04,570
Any questions on this?

1364
01:23:04,570 --> 01:23:05,070
Yeah.

1365
01:23:09,830 --> 01:23:11,570
All right, that's
a great question.

1366
01:23:11,570 --> 01:23:16,030
The question is,
what does head mean?

1367
01:23:16,030 --> 01:23:17,290
So I guess I went too fast.

1368
01:23:17,290 --> 01:23:18,650
I ignored that part.

1369
01:23:18,650 --> 01:23:24,910
But when you do the
self-attention computation,

1370
01:23:24,910 --> 01:23:29,550
you basically make queries
interact with keys,

1371
01:23:29,550 --> 01:23:32,120
and then take the
corresponding value.

1372
01:23:32,120 --> 01:23:36,480
But nothing prevents you from
doing that several times.

1373
01:23:36,480 --> 01:23:42,600
So the term "head" is given to
the projection matrices that you

1374
01:23:42,600 --> 01:23:46,080
use to obtain the
query, key, and value.

1375
01:23:46,080 --> 01:23:49,000
And when you have several
heads, what you're doing

1376
01:23:49,000 --> 01:23:55,520
is you're allowing your model
to learn different projections.

1377
01:23:55,520 --> 01:23:57,920
So it's basically
an additional degree

1378
01:23:57,920 --> 01:24:00,840
of freedom for your model to
learn different associations

1379
01:24:00,840 --> 01:24:03,240
between your vectors.

1380
01:24:03,240 --> 01:24:04,800
So it's a great question.

1381
01:24:04,800 --> 01:24:10,840
So typically it will be noted
lowercase h, number of heads.

1382
01:24:10,840 --> 01:24:13,840
And this is what
this corresponds to.

1383
01:24:13,840 --> 01:24:16,640
Does that answer your question?

1384
01:24:16,640 --> 01:24:20,030
Cool, very cool.

1385
01:24:23,644 --> 01:24:28,840
OK, we have a lot to
discuss, but here I

1386
01:24:28,840 --> 01:24:30,440
had the slide actually for this.

1387
01:24:30,440 --> 01:24:32,720
So this is the multi-heads
that you were mentioning.

1388
01:24:32,720 --> 01:24:35,940
So we're basically running
the self-attention computation

1389
01:24:35,940 --> 01:24:37,460
several times in
parallel, again,

1390
01:24:37,460 --> 01:24:42,780
with different projection
matrices that the model learns.

1391
01:24:42,780 --> 01:24:45,660
So in case you have a
computer vision background,

1392
01:24:45,660 --> 01:24:52,540
it is similar to having multiple
filters in your convolution.

1393
01:24:52,540 --> 01:24:58,260
So it's the same idea,
but it's different here.

1394
01:24:58,260 --> 01:25:07,320
Yeah, great question.

1395
01:25:07,320 --> 01:25:09,640
So the question is, are
the projections different?

1396
01:25:09,640 --> 01:25:13,340
So we're typically not
constraining things.

1397
01:25:13,340 --> 01:25:15,220
We're just letting
the model learn.

1398
01:25:15,220 --> 01:25:18,980
But in practice, it just
tends to learn different ways

1399
01:25:18,980 --> 01:25:21,620
of saying the same thing.

1400
01:25:21,620 --> 01:25:23,400
So yeah, typically
there is no constraint.

1401
01:25:23,400 --> 01:25:27,220
Of course, you have papers
that dig into how about

1402
01:25:27,220 --> 01:25:28,290
if you change this.

1403
01:25:28,290 --> 01:25:30,490
But typically you don't
have any constraint.

1404
01:25:34,190 --> 01:25:39,410
Cool, great.

1405
01:25:39,410 --> 01:25:41,570
OK, I will just
mention one trick,

1406
01:25:41,570 --> 01:25:45,710
another trick that the
transformer authors use.

1407
01:25:45,710 --> 01:25:49,950
So it's called label smoothing.

1408
01:25:49,950 --> 01:25:53,830
Who has heard of
label smoothing?

1409
01:25:53,830 --> 01:25:59,910
So one new thing
here is in NLP when

1410
01:25:59,910 --> 01:26:03,110
you want to predict
what comes next,

1411
01:26:03,110 --> 01:26:06,110
there's typically
more than one way.

1412
01:26:06,110 --> 01:26:09,510
When you say, what
a great day, what

1413
01:26:09,510 --> 01:26:12,970
a great lecture, what a
great book, what a great--

1414
01:26:12,970 --> 01:26:16,330
there's always multiple choices.

1415
01:26:16,330 --> 01:26:19,510
There's more than one
way of filling that gap.

1416
01:26:19,510 --> 01:26:21,070
So label smoothing
is a technique

1417
01:26:21,070 --> 01:26:25,570
that tries to
intuitively address that.

1418
01:26:25,570 --> 01:26:30,650
And what it does is, instead of
saying predict this word 100%

1419
01:26:30,650 --> 01:26:35,810
is this one, there is no other
words, what it does is it says,

1420
01:26:35,810 --> 01:26:40,250
predict this word, but there's
a chance it's not this word.

1421
01:26:40,250 --> 01:26:44,230
And in practice, what it does is
it takes the one-hot encoding.

1422
01:26:44,230 --> 01:26:46,890
And instead of saying
it's a 1, 0, 0, 0,

1423
01:26:46,890 --> 01:26:50,050
that you need to predict,
it says it's actually

1424
01:26:50,050 --> 01:26:56,993
1 minus epsilon, and then
epsilon over v minus 1, I guess,

1425
01:26:56,993 --> 01:26:58,160
is you're trying to predict.

1426
01:27:00,730 --> 01:27:06,450
So in practice,
it's a method that

1427
01:27:06,450 --> 01:27:09,737
tends to make your
model be more unsure.

1428
01:27:09,737 --> 01:27:11,570
Again, to be less sure
about this prediction

1429
01:27:11,570 --> 01:27:15,530
because you always tell it,
OK, try to predict this,

1430
01:27:15,530 --> 01:27:19,370
but actually it's possible
it's not the correct value.

1431
01:27:19,370 --> 01:27:22,610
But in practice, the
authors see that it

1432
01:27:22,610 --> 01:27:26,240
tends to improve
metrics like BLEU,

1433
01:27:26,240 --> 01:27:31,020
which is a proxy metric
for translation tasks.

1434
01:27:31,020 --> 01:27:35,040
So yeah, I think this method
is pretty general for NLP.

1435
01:27:35,040 --> 01:27:37,700
So yeah, it's a
good one to know.

1436
01:27:37,700 --> 01:27:42,840
And with that, I think there's
about 20-ish minutes left.

