how the transformer worked.

1470
01:29:39,930 --> 01:29:42,770
And now we're going to
piece it all together

1471
01:29:42,770 --> 01:29:46,410
with the one specific example.

1472
01:29:46,410 --> 01:29:47,530
OK, great.

1473
01:29:47,530 --> 01:29:49,870
So let's take our
favorite example again.

1474
01:29:49,870 --> 01:29:51,990
So a cute teddy bear is reading.

1475
01:29:51,990 --> 01:29:57,290
And then we'll go all
together through each step.

1476
01:29:57,290 --> 01:30:01,290
So first we start
with tokenization.

1477
01:30:01,290 --> 01:30:06,170
So as we said, we can use
any arbitrary decomposition

1478
01:30:06,170 --> 01:30:10,170
to decompose this into tokens.

1479
01:30:10,170 --> 01:30:12,010
And then as someone
mentioned, you

1480
01:30:12,010 --> 01:30:16,730
need to have some way to
indicate the start and the end

1481
01:30:16,730 --> 01:30:17,850
of a sequence.

1482
01:30:17,850 --> 01:30:21,750
So typically, this is done
with the BOS and EOS tokens.

1483
01:30:21,750 --> 01:30:22,690
So you add them.

1484
01:30:25,350 --> 01:30:27,670
So now let's focus
on the composition

1485
01:30:27,670 --> 01:30:30,670
of each token representation.

1486
01:30:30,670 --> 01:30:32,510
So you have its embedding.

1487
01:30:32,510 --> 01:30:33,990
That is learned.

1488
01:30:33,990 --> 01:30:36,710
And as Afshine
mentioned, in order

1489
01:30:36,710 --> 01:30:39,670
to have an idea of what is
the position of the words

1490
01:30:39,670 --> 01:30:42,710
or the token, I should say
as part of the sequence,

1491
01:30:42,710 --> 01:30:44,590
you have some added
information that

1492
01:30:44,590 --> 01:30:47,950
is in the form of a
position embedding.

1493
01:30:47,950 --> 01:30:51,750
And here, the original
paper uses the convention

1494
01:30:51,750 --> 01:30:56,070
of some sines and cosines
that it adds additively

1495
01:30:56,070 --> 01:30:58,090
to the representation.

1496
01:30:58,090 --> 01:31:01,910
So it's like an
element-wise addition.

1497
01:31:01,910 --> 01:31:02,890
OK, great.

1498
01:31:02,890 --> 01:31:07,830
So now you have a position-aware
embedding for your token.

1499
01:31:07,830 --> 01:31:11,350
And you repeat that for
each of your tokens.

1500
01:31:11,350 --> 01:31:15,310
So now you can see all
of these embeddings

1501
01:31:15,310 --> 01:31:19,440
in the format of a matrix,
which is of size d model, which

1502
01:31:19,440 --> 01:31:20,980
is the size of your embeddings.

1503
01:31:20,980 --> 01:31:23,640
And then the other
dimension is the length

1504
01:31:23,640 --> 01:31:26,900
of the sequence, so typically n.

1505
01:31:29,520 --> 01:31:31,920
So all make sense so far?

1506
01:31:31,920 --> 01:31:34,840
Any questions on the inputs?

1507
01:31:34,840 --> 01:31:36,200
OK, great.

1508
01:31:36,200 --> 01:31:39,280
So now we will send
this representation

1509
01:31:39,280 --> 01:31:41,880
through the encoder.

1510
01:31:41,880 --> 01:31:46,280
So as Afshine said, you have
this concept of self-attention.

1511
01:31:46,280 --> 01:31:48,400
And the way you
perform self-attention

1512
01:31:48,400 --> 01:31:54,720
is that you take this input
and project it on three spaces.

1513
01:31:54,720 --> 01:32:00,600
So you project it to the
space Wq, you get queries.

1514
01:32:00,600 --> 01:32:06,040
You project the same embeddings
in the space Wk, you get keys.

1515
01:32:06,040 --> 01:32:09,840
And you do the same for
values, you get your values.

1516
01:32:09,840 --> 01:32:14,740
And then Wq, Wk, and Wv
are learned by the model.

1517
01:32:14,740 --> 01:32:16,430
They are basically
projection matrices.

1518
01:32:19,300 --> 01:32:21,500
So far, so good?

1519
01:32:21,500 --> 01:32:24,620
So now with all of
that in mind, you

1520
01:32:24,620 --> 01:32:27,160
can apply the formula
that Afshine mentioned,

1521
01:32:27,160 --> 01:32:29,720
that is the
self-attention formula,

1522
01:32:29,720 --> 01:32:34,100
which is softmax of Qk
transpose over square root of dk

1523
01:32:34,100 --> 01:32:39,400
times v, which gives you another
matrix out of all of this.

1524
01:32:42,540 --> 01:32:45,860
Now let's pause for
a second and look

1525
01:32:45,860 --> 01:32:48,260
at how this computation
is done in practice

1526
01:32:48,260 --> 01:32:50,410
and what every step means.

1527
01:32:52,980 --> 01:32:56,660
So let's look at Q.
When you compute Q,

1528
01:32:56,660 --> 01:32:59,920
basically you project your
embeddings into that space.

1529
01:32:59,920 --> 01:33:00,800
What do you obtain?

1530
01:33:00,800 --> 01:33:07,780
You obtain a matrix where each
row represents a given query.

1531
01:33:07,780 --> 01:33:10,420
When you say k
transpose, it's basically

1532
01:33:10,420 --> 01:33:14,150
the same matrix, but
transposed, where

1533
01:33:14,150 --> 01:33:19,270
each column represents the key
representation of each token.

1534
01:33:19,270 --> 01:33:25,870
Now let's mix them together
with the matrix multiplication.

1535
01:33:25,870 --> 01:33:28,230
So when you multiply
each of them,

1536
01:33:28,230 --> 01:33:32,270
you see that each row
represents the projection

1537
01:33:32,270 --> 01:33:42,270
of the query over each key, such
that when you take the matrix

1538
01:33:42,270 --> 01:33:44,810
multiplication and get the
softmax of all of this,

1539
01:33:44,810 --> 01:33:46,750
you get a probability
distribution

1540
01:33:46,750 --> 01:33:51,990
of the projection of the query
over keys for each query.

1541
01:33:51,990 --> 01:33:55,710
Each line will have this.

1542
01:33:55,710 --> 01:33:59,670
And I don't know if anyone asked
the question regarding why do we

1543
01:33:59,670 --> 01:34:03,190
scale by square root of dk?

1544
01:34:03,190 --> 01:34:07,590
So it could be dq as well
because matrix multiplication,

1545
01:34:07,590 --> 01:34:09,470
like the dot product
here, enforces

1546
01:34:09,470 --> 01:34:12,400
the fact that dq equals dk.

1547
01:34:12,400 --> 01:34:16,560
And basically, what you see
is that these dot products has

1548
01:34:16,560 --> 01:34:19,040
the dimension of key
and queries grows,

1549
01:34:19,040 --> 01:34:20,460
it will tend to grow as well.

1550
01:34:20,460 --> 01:34:23,500
So you want to normalize
these dot products.

1551
01:34:23,500 --> 01:34:26,120
And this is why you
divide by square root

1552
01:34:26,120 --> 01:34:30,560
of the dimension of keys.

1553
01:34:30,560 --> 01:34:31,760
OK, great.

1554
01:34:31,760 --> 01:34:34,860
And then now you have your
softmax of all of these,

1555
01:34:34,860 --> 01:34:37,280
and then you multiply
it with the matrix

1556
01:34:37,280 --> 01:34:45,600
v. And this is Afshine explained
as having the query projected

1557
01:34:45,600 --> 01:34:48,560
on the space of keys,
and then multiplied

1558
01:34:48,560 --> 01:34:49,860
by the corresponding value.

1559
01:34:49,860 --> 01:34:52,120
So the value is
the representation

1560
01:34:52,120 --> 01:34:55,840
of the corresponding
key that we project on.

1561
01:34:55,840 --> 01:35:00,630
So you end up with a weighted
sum of values for each query.

1562
01:35:03,680 --> 01:35:05,600
OK, great.

1563
01:35:05,600 --> 01:35:06,940
Does that make sense so far?

1564
01:35:12,180 --> 01:35:13,540
OK, awesome.

1565
01:35:13,540 --> 01:35:17,480
And someone asked, what
is the multi-head stuff?

1566
01:35:17,480 --> 01:35:20,620
So you're right, it's not
just single one, one time

1567
01:35:20,620 --> 01:35:21,280
that it's done.

1568
01:35:21,280 --> 01:35:23,780
It's actually done each times.

1569
01:35:23,780 --> 01:35:28,020
And what you obtain is, like,
all of that is done in parallel.

1570
01:35:28,020 --> 01:35:33,140
And at the end, you
obtain h such matrices.

1571
01:35:33,140 --> 01:35:37,180
And you concatenate them
with respect to the columns.

1572
01:35:37,180 --> 01:35:40,620
And at the end of this, you
have another projection matrix

1573
01:35:40,620 --> 01:35:45,580
that you call Wo that will
project all of these back

1574
01:35:45,580 --> 01:35:49,540
to the original
dimension of embeddings.

1575
01:35:49,540 --> 01:35:53,100
So it's a way for the
network to basically have

1576
01:35:53,100 --> 01:35:55,540
a dimension-invariant way--

1577
01:35:55,540 --> 01:35:59,460
bless you-- to go from
the original dimension

1578
01:35:59,460 --> 01:36:03,140
back to the original one.

1579
01:36:03,140 --> 01:36:05,320
Any questions?

1580
01:36:05,320 --> 01:36:05,820
Yep.

1581
01:36:15,750 --> 01:36:18,090
So the question is regarding h.

1582
01:36:18,090 --> 01:36:20,370
Is it possible to get the
same result each time?

1583
01:36:20,370 --> 01:36:24,022
And if so, concatenate the
same thing, will it be helpful?

1584
01:36:24,022 --> 01:36:25,230
Did I get the question right?

1585
01:36:28,030 --> 01:36:29,290
So what makes it different?

1586
01:36:29,290 --> 01:36:32,350
So it's the magic
of gradient descent.

1587
01:36:32,350 --> 01:36:34,970
So the network has an
objective function at the end.

1588
01:36:34,970 --> 01:36:36,750
It has degrees of freedom.

1589
01:36:36,750 --> 01:36:39,910
Its incentive is to build a
representation that will be

1590
01:36:39,910 --> 01:36:42,310
helpful to learn the next word.

1591
01:36:42,310 --> 01:36:44,870
So it doesn't have an incentive
to copy the same thing

1592
01:36:44,870 --> 01:36:46,550
or do the same mechanism.

1593
01:36:46,550 --> 01:36:50,590
And this is why in practice
you see the model converge

1594
01:36:50,590 --> 01:36:53,990
towards building different
representations that it can then

1595
01:36:53,990 --> 01:36:57,130
concatenate and then project
into something useful.

1596
01:36:57,130 --> 01:37:00,650
So what makes it such that
you don't have the same thing?

1597
01:37:00,650 --> 01:37:01,470
Nothing.

1598
01:37:01,470 --> 01:37:03,170
Like, you don't have
any constraints.

1599
01:37:03,170 --> 01:37:08,250
But the nature of the learning
that you let the model have

1600
01:37:08,250 --> 01:37:09,860
makes it do so in practice.

1601
01:37:14,370 --> 01:37:17,450
Any other questions?

1602
01:37:17,450 --> 01:37:19,430
And that is a great question.

1603
01:37:19,430 --> 01:37:25,530
I mean, typically gradient
descent does wonders.

1604
01:37:25,530 --> 01:37:27,570
OK great.

1605
01:37:27,570 --> 01:37:31,210
So now that we have gone through
the self-attention layer,

1606
01:37:31,210 --> 01:37:34,810
you have another
component that is the FFN.

1607
01:37:34,810 --> 01:37:37,530
And I think there was a
question just here regarding

1608
01:37:37,530 --> 01:37:39,890
how to choose the dimension
of the hidden layer

1609
01:37:39,890 --> 01:37:41,970
with respect to the
input and outputs.

1610
01:37:41,970 --> 01:37:44,370
So when Afshine
mentioned Word2vec,

1611
01:37:44,370 --> 01:37:46,410
typically you have
a smaller dimension

1612
01:37:46,410 --> 01:37:48,650
than the input and output.

1613
01:37:48,650 --> 01:37:51,210
But here, actually,
the hidden layer

1614
01:37:51,210 --> 01:37:54,810
is of a bigger dimension
than input and output.

1615
01:37:54,810 --> 01:37:57,050
And the rationale
for that is that you

1616
01:37:57,050 --> 01:38:00,810
want to have enough degrees of
freedom for the model to learn

1617
01:38:00,810 --> 01:38:03,170
useful representations.

1618
01:38:03,170 --> 01:38:06,780
So it's a way to complexify
the features that you learn.

1619
01:38:06,780 --> 01:38:10,540
And, yeah [INAUDIBLE].

1620
01:38:10,540 --> 01:38:11,980
OK, great.

1621
01:38:11,980 --> 01:38:15,160
And you don't have just
one encoder module.

1622
01:38:15,160 --> 01:38:19,460
You have actually n of them,
big N in the original paper.

1623
01:38:19,460 --> 01:38:21,540
And at the end of
all of this, you

1624
01:38:21,540 --> 01:38:27,060
have an encoded context-aware
set of embeddings.

1625
01:38:27,060 --> 01:38:30,020
And then each of
these setups encoded

1626
01:38:30,020 --> 01:38:35,660
embeddings will be those that
will be fed to the n decoders.

1627
01:38:35,660 --> 01:38:41,040
So you have like a stacked
succession of n encoders.

1628
01:38:41,040 --> 01:38:43,900
You have a stacked
succession of n decoders.

1629
01:38:43,900 --> 01:38:46,260
And the last representation
of the encoder

1630
01:38:46,260 --> 01:38:49,990
is what you will feed to the
cross-attention of each decoder.

1631
01:38:54,340 --> 01:38:57,700
So yeah, we're going to
see that more in detail.

1632
01:38:57,700 --> 01:39:01,520
So how do we even start
the decoding process?

1633
01:39:01,520 --> 01:39:03,400
So you start with the BOS token.

1634
01:39:03,400 --> 01:39:06,040
Basically saying to
the model, hey, we

1635
01:39:06,040 --> 01:39:10,320
need to predict the
next word, let's start.

1636
01:39:10,320 --> 01:39:14,320
So what happens to the BOS
token at the very beginning?

1637
01:39:14,320 --> 01:39:16,340
So you feed it to the decoder.

1638
01:39:16,340 --> 01:39:18,880
And then similarly as
before for the encoder,

1639
01:39:18,880 --> 01:39:21,160
you have a self-attention layer.

1640
01:39:21,160 --> 01:39:27,240
And as Afshine mentioned, the
self-attention layer is causal.

1641
01:39:27,240 --> 01:39:30,760
So the attention will be
done on the same token

1642
01:39:30,760 --> 01:39:33,040
and the tokens that precede it.

1643
01:39:33,040 --> 01:39:36,280
So on this first BOS token,
you don't see a difference,

1644
01:39:36,280 --> 01:39:38,520
because it will just
attend to itself.

1645
01:39:38,520 --> 01:39:42,720
But when you have other tokens
that you want to decode,

1646
01:39:42,720 --> 01:39:45,280
you will have this
difference in where you

1647
01:39:45,280 --> 01:39:48,840
attend with respect to decoder.

1648
01:39:48,840 --> 01:39:51,880
OK, great, goes through
the self-attention layer.

1649
01:39:51,880 --> 01:39:53,800
And then you have
what I mentioned

1650
01:39:53,800 --> 01:40:01,090
to be the cross-attention
that takes as keys and values

1651
01:40:01,090 --> 01:40:04,530
these encoded
embeddings as inputs.

1652
01:40:04,530 --> 01:40:08,530
And then the queries
are those that come out

1653
01:40:08,530 --> 01:40:12,330
of the self-attention layer.

1654
01:40:12,330 --> 01:40:13,730
OK, great.

1655
01:40:13,730 --> 01:40:15,930
And then once you do
this cross-attention,

1656
01:40:15,930 --> 01:40:18,330
you have, just like
in the encoder,

1657
01:40:18,330 --> 01:40:22,910
an FFN component that makes
the representation richer.

1658
01:40:22,910 --> 01:40:24,070
Was there a question there?

1659
01:40:24,070 --> 01:40:24,570
No.

1660
01:40:28,210 --> 01:40:32,270
And then at the very end, so
you do all of that n times.

1661
01:40:32,270 --> 01:40:34,390
And at the very end of
the decoding process,

1662
01:40:34,390 --> 01:40:37,810
you have a linear projection
and a softmax layer

1663
01:40:37,810 --> 01:40:40,930
to turn the prediction
of the next word

1664
01:40:40,930 --> 01:40:46,370
into a probability distribution
over the vocabulary.

1665
01:40:46,370 --> 01:40:46,870
OK, great.

1666
01:40:46,870 --> 01:40:50,130
So we saw how to do that
for the next word here.

1667
01:40:50,130 --> 01:40:54,230
And basically you do
that again and again.

1668
01:40:54,230 --> 01:40:58,370
So you have found
your next token,

1669
01:40:58,370 --> 01:41:02,350
which is like a
one-hot basically

1670
01:41:02,350 --> 01:41:03,890
encoding of what you want.

1671
01:41:03,890 --> 01:41:06,710
And then you take that
embedding and then put it back

1672
01:41:06,710 --> 01:41:10,470
in the decoder and
continue this process.

1673
01:41:10,470 --> 01:41:13,670
And when do you stop?

1674
01:41:13,670 --> 01:41:17,110
It's a question for you all.

1675
01:41:17,110 --> 01:41:18,730
When you hit the EOS token.

1676
01:41:18,730 --> 01:41:23,070
Yeah, yeah exactly.

1677
01:41:23,070 --> 01:41:24,550
OK, great.

1678
01:41:24,550 --> 01:41:27,390
And with this process,
it's basically

1679
01:41:27,390 --> 01:41:31,990
how the authors of this
original landmark paper

1680
01:41:31,990 --> 01:41:33,690
did machine translation.

1681
01:41:33,690 --> 01:41:37,550
So this is typically the
use case that was presented.

1682
01:41:37,550 --> 01:41:39,010
Any questions?

1683
01:41:45,430 --> 01:41:47,310
OK, awesome.

1684
01:41:47,310 --> 01:41:49,990
And with that, thank
you for your attention.

1685
01:41:49,990 --> 01:41:54,240
[APPLAUSE]